Parliament does not support the amendment that gives Tymoshenko his freedom
Today, the Ukrainian Parliament, in the course of amending the Criminal Procedure Code, rejected an attempt to repeal the article that convicted opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko.
An amendment that would have led to the release of the jailed former prime minister was rejected during the second reading of a bill to reduce sentences for economic offenses.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for signing a gas deal with Russia that was deemed unprofitable.
The verdict is not final; the court will hear Tymoshenko's appeal in December.
Tymoshenko argues that the sentence is a political revenge of the regime; the West also suspected bias in the process.
The motion to repeal Article 365 of the Criminal Procedure Code, under which the former prime minister was convicted, was supported by 147 members of Parliament.
It would require 226 votes to ratify.
