Nutrition for children with obesity: No breakfast and no sausage for dinner
More than a third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 are overweight; while 9% of schoolchildren are overweight, 5% are obese.
According to a recent study, children who are obese tend to come from families with unhealthy lifestyles.
We see once again the importance of the environment and the behavioral patterns that accompany a person for his or her healthy development.
For example, sausages are on the tables of children who are obese almost twice as often as those in families with children of normal weight.
More than 19 percent of obese children ate French fries for dinner the day before a survey for an educational event called Obesity is no accident.
Moreover, families with children who are obese do not exercise, but this is true of most families of today's schoolchildren - only 15 percent of children said that their parents make time to exercise at least once a week.
The study was conducted among 900 children.
The study was conducted at the end of last school year and involved nearly 900 primary school pupils from all over Bohemia.
The event Obesity is not an accident was held for the second year in a row, with the support of the insurance company Všeobecná zdravotní pojišťovna and Unilever.
To date, more than 12 thousand students from 4th to 8th grade have joined the project.
Proper nutrition and adequate exercise are the major determinants of the rapidly increasing number of children who are either overweight or obese.
"For example, only half of the respondents said they ate five meals a day, breakfast-breakfast-lunch-breakfast-dinner, which is a prerequisite for proper nutrition", says one study.
No lunch and no sausage in the evenings.
Experts warn that even such relative details as a regular family breakfast are important for healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of school families have breakfast together.
In most families, everyone eats breakfast separately.
The worst finding was that one in ten families didn't have breakfast at all.
Yet, breakfast is the foundation of a proper daily diet.
The study found that fried food is more common in families with children who are obese.
Almost everyone , regardless of weight , drinks a sweet beverage every day (70%).
Although more than 40 percent of children regularly participate in sports, this figure drops more than half - to 15 percent - when it comes to their parents.
Make your own menu.
In another part of the study, the children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) were asked to create their own menu based on the food they were offered and their tastes and preferences.
"The food preferences of Czech children aged 12-15 are far from ideal when it comes to healthy eating".
Their favorite food includes a large number of flour, meat, and sweet dishes.
"The high popularity of sugary soft drinks is of particular concern", the study concludes.
As the main meal, pasta beat the slightly heavier bird.
However, the children showed little interest in legumes, fish, and vegetables.
A healthy lifestyle
The study also showed that children are willing to change their eating habits if they are given appropriate information.
"Many of the study's controls showed a significant shift in their preferences toward healthy food when they completed the questionnaire after the lecture.
This was particularly noticeable, for example, in the case of sugary soft drinks, where more children preferred water.
In addition, the children often noted poultry and fish as the main dishes, limiting the amount of sweet foods and pastries.
A stylist must also be a good psychologist, say the professionals.
In my first article on stylist training, I was puzzled by the amount of information in the introductory classes.
I had no idea what was coming next.
Three lectures from experts in the field; tips on how to dress for a different figure; and a seminar on how it all works in real life.
More to come.
The closer we get to the final exam, the more information and practical assignments await us.
Training is every Saturday and Sunday, but it's really rich with information.
This time, with the principal, Alenka, (there are no men in the class) we discussed how to dress a woman whose body is not perfectly symmetrical.
Most women are not completely symmetrical.
One has a short neck, another has a boyish figure without proper forms, another weighs more than normal.
A stylist must know how to visually reduce the shoulders, lengthen the neck, or add the missing volume.
We were given advice on how to enhance the figure of women like Jennifer Lopez, who have bigger breasts and thighs and a narrower waist, without wearing too provocative.
For example, if the waist and hips are so different that you cannot choose a skirt or pants, you should have at least one item made to order.
You will certainly not regret the investment, for a perfectly fitting garment is priceless.
A custom-made skirt will make you feel much better than one that's always squeezing, rolling, exposing your waist, etc.
Women with boy figures, on the other hand, may wear clothes with ruffles, applications, embroidery or folds.
Given the abundance of this information and the types of figures, I'm glad I have a whole week to figure it all out.
And yet, I'm afraid it's too much, given the homework we've been given.
Each participant had to design two outfits for a celebrity: one for the day and one for the evening.
We must take into account their modern appearance, their style of dress, and their figure.
I'm going to dress Miranda Kerr, who you may know from Victoria's Secret campaigns.
I'm happy for myself because it's so much easier to wear than, say, Britney Spears, Christina Aguilera, who recently gained a ton (please bear in mind that I'm exaggerating), or a very young Selena Gomez.
We have to cut clothes out of magazines or find them online, print them and process them with graphics software.
The mudboard, the result of the work, reflects our own style and attitude towards the graphic.
It's important to keep in mind the graphic component of the style.
The stylist doesn't just dress real people, but creates product pages in magazines (based on specific instructions, such as fashionable bags, coats, etc.).
That's what the stylist and designer Mario Kamenik told us.
But it was only on Sunday.
A stylist needs general knowledge .
The Saturday lecture, which was rich in information on the types of figures, was brought to life by three guests - experts in the field.
Stylist, Honza Pokorna; fashion designer, Jacob Polanka; and fashion photographer Ben Rench. He is also a fashion designer.
Jacob reminded us that fashion is an illusion and the stylist must use that fact.
A good stylist knows how to use one item of clothing in different ways.
In this case, diversity is the key to success.
For example, a trench coat can be worn normally over jeans and a T-shirt, like a coat; but it can also be worn on the naked body, without clasps, like a dress.
Or you can roll up your sleeves or lift up your collar and the whole picture changes.
"Play with it", he insisted.
Anyway, the advice I appreciated most was, "You have to know the rules of your job perfectly".
Then you can start breaking them,' Jacob told us.
And here I finally understood why we're so obsessed with definitions and rules, what to combine with what and why, when in fashion magazines we often see something completely different.
Not to mention the fashion show.
I learned from Ben, the photographer, that a stylist should have more options than the number of photos he needs to take.
So, for a ten-page fashion review (equivalent to ten outfits), I have to be prepared to create at least fifteen images.
Now I also know that in a picture, an item of clothing often looks and functions differently from the way it does in reality.
We have to keep that in mind when we create an image.
Honza Pokorny confirmed that often image and style are half the success.
Just look at Madonna, who doesn't have a great vocal range, but her image and marketing have made her a global star.
Attitudes toward stylists in the Czech Republic are still quite cool.
Even famous people often consider it superfluous (and believe that being an expert in something is enough, and how they look is secondary).
And if someone finally lets us create their style, we should expect them to give us a different size than the one they actually wear.
Then we go to Google and see if there's been any tabloid stories about some celebrity gaining weight or losing weight, etc.
On Sunday, both Honza and Mario emphasized that it is not enough for a stylist to know fashion and be able to pick out an outfit.
Our work is mostly about interacting with the people we dress; so it's important to be a good psychologist.
To be able to judge people, not to be condescending and to hold your own.
"If the manager asks you to go through her clothes and add a few nice things, you can't throw away her entire wardrobe by telling her her clothes suck".
"Find at least a few things you can commend and suggest what you can wear with them", says Mario.
He also showed us what specifically a work bag should fit.
It's a bag that you tie around your waist to carry everything you need.
In addition to obvious items such as scissors, sticky rolls, or English pins, it should have a nylon thread (stylesmen use it when shooting some items, such as a bag or hat), special clips to fasten fabric on the back in case the clothes are too large (sticks and similar items are prohibited, as they wear clothes) or a sewing kit.
To distract from the lecture and gain some practical experience, we learned how to make the correct shoe pads.
Even when shooting in a studio with a smooth floor, the soles can get damaged - not to mention shooting outside.
So we're in the process of putting the tape on.
You shouldn't touch the shoes with scissors, or you'll ruin them.
It takes real skill.
I was pleased that Mario praised my work.
I didn't like the skills you mentioned.
That's just part of what we heard during the second part of the weekend class.
I'm starting to realize that being a professional stylist isn't easy, no matter what people say.
V Need for Speed: Escape is set in America.
The review
What should have been a carefree walk has become a routine morning commute to work because of a series of completely inappropriate and careless mistakes.
The ambitions were met to some extent, but that didn't matter, because no one was obviously willing to do extra work.
Before the release of the new version with the subtitle "Flight" were attached great hopes.
It was expected to move the previous Need For Speed series in a new direction; the demo versions indicated that the game would take its rightful place in the racing game genre.
We were curious to see the parts of the game where the protagonist gets out of the car and runs.
As is often the case with NFS, the end result is a lot different than we expected.
The game is a fairly good arcade racer, but the overall impression is spoiled by a few unnecessary mistakes that have been present in this series of games for several years.
So, in reality, these are not errors, but the manifestation of inexplicable laziness of the developers.
The adventure starts off very well.
You become part of a story where the protagonist, Jack, decides to solve some personal problems by taking part in an illegal race across America.
You get in a car on the West Coast in San Francisco, and your job is to get to New York first.
There are some interesting things about this idea.
The route consists of ten stages, divided into more than fifty races.
This means that each race runs on its own route, with individual stages taking place in a diverse and interesting environment.
So it doesn't feel like the game is always the same.
Although the schedule is at the same level as in previous installments of the series, some tracks are enjoyable to watch.
Yet, the game does not evoke strong emotions.
Although driving through the desert, the autumn suburbs, or high in the snow-capped mountains is a pleasure.
And the race occasionally brings an unusual detail to life.
For example, in the desert, you're caught in a sandstorm that significantly reduces visibility.
On the other hand, in the mountains, you have to be careful not to fall under an avalanche.
The individual races are pretty well organized.
There are only a few varieties, but that's enough.
For a while you try to outrun several competitors (essentially a regular race); then you try to improve the time (standard race with a stopwatch); or you compete with one opponent.
You also run into the police from time to time, which makes your job even more difficult.
The components on the outside of the car are new.
It's just an interactive animation where most of the time Jack is running away from someone and you have to help him by pressing the right buttons at the right time.
It's not that hard.
Although surprisingly, these fragments are much smaller than you might expect (only three to be exact).
It actually turns out that this is good for the game because it's not boring, and that's one of the things that makes the game more fun.
The racing model follows in the footsteps of the previous models.
It means that she's no longer special, but that can't be considered a flaw.
If you're looking for a simulation of real life, you'll have to look elsewhere.
And yet this driving model is very suitable for dynamic racing, although better options can be found on the market.
So far so good.
But after a while, problems begin.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is not so good.
You don't expect a game like this to be complex and to have a lot of transformation and collisions, but if you have no idea how your car will behave before you hit an object, something is wrong.
Usually, when you're passing or overtaking cars in a traffic jam, you'll occasionally touch another car slightly, and yet sometimes in a similar situation, your car will start to spin wildly.
Or it was shattered.
It's not that important because of the reboot system, but it's enough to ruin the fun.
The restarts are designed so that if you crash or stray far off the track, the game will take you back to where it left off.
However, only five reboots are available for each race.
If you use them all, you'll have to start the race from the beginning.
It's useful in case something goes wrong, but you can't rely on it completely.
Sometimes restarting isn't enough, and you have to memorize a specific part of the race.
A major drawback of the game is the fact that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, some turns have to be done a certain way, otherwise you just don't fit in.
In other cases, you'll find civilian cars in a certain location in the same configuration whether you're first, fifth, five seconds early or a minute late.
This is especially annoying in situations where you see your opponent easily pass between two cars moving in opposite directions, whereas when you get there, the cars are already in position so you either have to go around them or slow down.
It doesn't matter when you're around them; everything is set up so that the situation always happens right under your nose.
The competition has other advantages.
During the game, you discover several locations where, regardless of time, the same opponent is overtaking you in the same place.
This is especially evident at the end of the game, on a long bridge, where you're driving in the opposite direction.
Obviously, your opponent has to stand up to you no matter what.
The thing is, when it's driving in front of you, it's going to affect your view, which leads to one or more accidents in that area.
You can understand trying to make the game more exciting and adrenaline-filled, but it's so obvious that it quickly becomes irritating.
It's a shame, because despite the simple driving pattern, the game is fun and sometimes so full of action that you don't have time to pay attention to what's going on around you.
It doesn't matter what you're not bored of, a concept with 50 unique tracks, a racing sequence or something else.
The idea of changing cars during a race is unusual.
You need to keep track of the gas stations along the way, because they are where your car can be replaced, even though in most cases the one you already have is quite sufficient.
The machines are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are great for cities; high-powered American cars are great for straight stretches of highway; and exotic super sports cars are great for technical driving, like on curved mountain tracks.
The main story mode is closely related to the challenge mode; it is racing through individual areas that you learn about as the game progresses.
Here you earn both medals and points for your personal cause, common to challenges and story modes.
There are many options available to get a higher level of driving: from cars to profile data.
In addition, the profile is linked to the online Autolog function, which, among other things, compares your results with those of other players and provides a connection with the public.
Here's another flaw that's hard to understand; this is an example from the last race in the sequence.
You and your car get into a subway tunnel (let's say so) where you race along the tracks in the dark (let's say so).
Your speedometer shows a figure of 150 to 200 kilometers per hour (let's say that's it) when suddenly a subway train hits you from behind, turning your car into a pile of scrap metal.
For days, our editorial staff debated whether it was really that nobody thought for a second while the game was being made, or whether the creators really thought we were such fools.
The game's technical aspects are not particularly good, but the overall experience is mostly pleasant, sometimes even amazing.
Although it's unfortunate that at some critical moments the quality of the recording, sometimes quite dramatically, declines.
This is especially true in large-scale events, where a good recording would not be very helpful either.
Sound is fine; the soundtrack is for the amateur.
To appeal to a wider audience of young people, the soundtrack 'includes compositions from different styles'; but it is unlikely that many people will buy the game because of its music.
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run is rather messy.
If the game avoided obviously unnecessary mistakes, we could honestly say that Escape is the best part of NFS in the last few years.
Either way, the game leaves a feeling of incompleteness.
Sure, it's good fun, but be prepared for the shortcomings to blind you like an airport beacon.
The Karlov University Choir will perform at the "Students in Velvet" concert
For the third year running, Festa Academia is combining International Student Day and the anniversary of the Velvet Revolution with a musical event.
He's gonna be performing with about twenty school and university choirs.
