The ambassador to the EU , Visenova:
The Czechs have a reputation for being unfriendly and skeptical of the euro.
"The Treaty of Lisbon caused considerable disagreement between the various organizations".
"I didn't expect it to be such a brutal war".
"It will take five or six years before the situation is stabilized, calmed down and all the players get used to their new roles", EU Ambassador Milena Vitsenova began her lecture at the law school with a sharp start.
She proved how committed she is to her motto "Clear and Open about Europe" in the very first part of her lecture, where she described the individual EU institutions and their relations in a way that many lecturers at the KU Law School would envy.
Moreover, Vicenova praised the work of the new permanent president of the European Council, Herman Van Rompuy:
"At first, critics said he was just a gray office mouse who couldn't play any role; I have to say, everyone was amazed at how well he handled his role".
"He is a man who can listen to the 27 participating countries at the same time, communicates well with them and has a clear idea of the direction in which the EU should develop".
She explained her new position as the EU's representative for international relations and security as an answer to the question: 'Who is the European Union?
No one is going to ban our cheese.
Vitsenova further focused on a programme that is key to the EU's past, present and near future.
She called the Czech presidency a successful one the year before.
The Czechs were dealing with the impending financial crisis; they overcame that crisis and organized the Eastern Partnership summit.
She said that the resignation of the government at the time was a negative phenomenon that caused considerable damage to the Czech Republic.
The Czech representatives in the EU are currently very busy.
As the ambassador said, both the presidency and the ensuing financial crisis have caused the current ferment.
It is also necessary to adopt a new seven-year EU budget, which is very difficult given the current crisis.
Whether the budget will be tight and economical, which areas will be given priority, which countries will receive more support and which less; all these issues are in the forthcoming programme.
The Ambassador recalled the key slogans she had brought to Brussels: "About Europe, in a clear language".
"I really don't like abbreviations, foreign words, and jargon that nobody understands.
How can citizens understand that in Brussels people are not trying to sell curved or round cucumbers, bananas of different sizes, or that someone is going to ban our cheese varieties.'
It also intends to make more efficient use of the EU environment and attract more Czechs to European organisations.
A high-speed Europe is our future
The ambassador claims that Czechs are considered Euro-skeptics; as well as people who note the negative rather than the positive sides of things.
She wants more Czech representatives to be involved in European organizations.
She believes that several factors are to blame: for example, the modesty of our candidates and their inability to write motivation letters; at the same time with little support from the Czech side.
Alongside the successful Czech presidency, she noted the power and cooperation of the Visegrad Group.
"Believe me, when I meet someone from Poland or Hungary and a Slovak joins us, the Frenchman next to me says, 'Hey, what's the meeting about, the Visegrad group again?' and he's not happy about it.'
In the future, the Vitsenov Union expects mainly new strict rules for the budgetary policy of the member states.
Compared with the new European Federation, she considers the idea of a two-speed, if not a multi-speed Europe more realistic.
"We have both countries inside and outside the Eurozone".
"We have the Schengen area, and we already have the institution of enhanced cooperation".
"For the first time, it was said that countries that wanted to unite should, while those that did not, could stay out".
"The number of such institutions will grow; it will be a truly two-speed Europe", expects Vicenova.
In this respect, she stressed the role of both the Czech Republic and Herman Van Rompuy in promoting the rule that all EU-wide issues should be discussed by all member countries, not just those in the eurozone.
The history of the brand:
IBM is entering its second century of innovation.
If anyone wants to find the word that best expresses the IMB strategy, the closest one is probably "long-term".
IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution for the general public; the company is considered very modern, although it was founded more than a hundred years ago.
The company's longevity was built on the foundation of its first boss, visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He believed in his motto that many of the world's problems could be easily solved if people would just think.
His slogan "Think!" thus became the stamp around which the life of the future giant unfolded (as well as the title of his internal journal, which IMB began publishing in 1935).
Moreover, it was the foundation of a corporate culture that Watson carefully built.
"For us at IBM, long-term thinking means moving forward.
IBM survived and thrived for a hundred years because it remained true to its original values, even though it wasn't afraid to change everything around it.
In our first 100 years, it allowed us to transform technology, business and company.
In the next hundred years, we hope to do even more", says Samuel J. Palmisano, the company's current CEO, on the occasion of the anniversary.
A complicated system
In the 1930s, Watson approached employee care in the same way that Batea had in the Czech Republic - IMB employees were among the first American employees with paid leave, employer insurance, elegant uniforms, and a complex bonus system for top inventors and entrepreneurs.
Equally advanced are IBM's long-term relationships with consumers.
From the very beginning, the company found brilliant uses for talented people, and it was one of the first companies in the world to eliminate all discrimination, which gave it great choice.
Consistent with the anti-discrimination strategy and current plan, a woman, Virginia Rometti, will succeed Palmisano next year.
She worked at IBM for thirty years; she is currently the director of sales, marketing and development.
For the past few years, IBM has been hosting meetings, online brainstorming sessions, that have spawned many future innovations.
It's no surprise that there are so many ideas -- the company has about half a million employees.
A reputable organization
The company's strong position in business is ensured by a strong internal and external image.
"From the beginning, IBM was more of an organization than a technology company in terms of concept", said Harvard Business School professor and IBM author Rosabeth Moss Kanter.
"IBM is not a technology company, it's a company that helps solve business problems with technology", adds George Colony of Forrester Research.
As the company says, there's a difference between going to market and creating a market.
In a hundred years, IBM, or the "Blue Giant", as it's called in the United States because of its logo, has become one of the largest companies in the world.
It seems to be the most versatile technology company -- developing hardware and software; infrastructure; hosting and consulting services -- from servers to nanotechnology.
It has the most patents of any American technology company, and five of its employees have won Nobel Prizes.
Her inventions include, for example, the ATM, the bank card, the financial swap, the barcode and the floppy disk.
With $220 billion in market capitalization, IBM this year became the second-largest technology company (first place is held by Apple), overtaking Microsoft for the first time since 1996.
Looking ahead
Not all of its products were to the taste of the customers and fit into the era.
"If your business is defined by moving forward, you can't be emotionally attached to the past", says Samuel J. Palmisano.
That's why IBM easily lays the foundation on multiple platforms -- if they don't work, it throws them out.
This is what makes it different from, say, its competitor Microsoft, which is based on and survives the crashes on Windows, its operating system.
Prospective technology
IBM's primary revenue comes from services, about one-fifth of which in each case comes from computer software and hardware.
Whereas in 1990, with half the capital, it was the strongest equipment manufacturing company.
Since 2000, IBM has sold $15 billion worth of low-yield assets, while investing $58 billion in new technology.
It continued to invest even after 2008, when the world was first hit by the current economic crisis.
IBM follows the example of its first CEO, Thomas J. Watson, who increased investment during the Great Depression.
So far, IBM seems to have been unharmed by the current crisis.
Since the beginning of 2008, IBM's stock price has risen by a record 120 percent; the company's net income has been steadily rising.
IBM's corporate motto is to change everything but your own values.
So it's to be expected that even if another crisis does break out, this resilient giant will be able to handle the situation.
The history of IBM: from the cheese knife to space flight.
IBM was founded in New York a hundred years ago, and its original name was "Computing, Tabling, Writing Corporation".
It took the name IBM in 1924, originally a brand name used for the company's offices in Canada and South America.
The foundation of the future IBM was laid by the merger of four companies whose history dates back to the 1880s.
They had technology like the legendary "table clock", a clock that kept track of when employees came and went from work.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlet Flint, who also headed the company's board of trustees until 1930.
Flint hired a director of a competing company, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
The CEO then pushed the founder of IBM into the shadows - Watson's ideas remain the basis of an unshakable corporate culture and personality.
Watson led the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, started out manufacturing and selling a variety of business equipment, from cheese knives and meat cleavers to cash registers.
In the first four years of Watson's leadership, revenues doubled to $9 million, and the company began a massive expansion into all continents.
Watson became so important to the company that almost forty years later his son, Thomas Watson Jr., took his place as chairman.
Under his leadership, IBM began developing artificial intelligence technologies and created the first programming language.
In the 1960s, both employees and IBM computers helped NASA monitor spaceflight -- to Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969 -- the manned flight to the Moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers - the IBM line System/360.
The classic PC that defined the computer standards of the time, called the IBM 5150, came on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold computer manufacturing to the Chinese company Lenovo, while simultaneously buying the consulting arm of PricewaterhouseCoopers, thus fully concentrating on consulting and high value-added services.
Over the last three years, IBM has made great strides with its Smarter Planet concept.
Its goal is to use technology wisely in areas where it has not yet been planned and to improve road conditions and city governance.
In the commercial sector, IBM recently introduced the Smarter Commerce platform, which helps business owners control the entire trading cycle.
IBM's traditions are strong even in our country.
In the former Czechoslovakia, as the first country to be located simultaneously in central and eastern Europe, IBM established its own branch in 1932.
Today IBM CZ also operates a strategic outsourcing centre in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe are in Prague, where a world-class speech recognition research group is also based.
