Travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, only five state tourist agencies could operate in the former Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Since travel to the West was strictly limited, travel agencies of the time mainly sold tours to the countries of the socialist bloc.
Thus, Czech tourists went on vacation to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea on the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both countries on the Black Sea); and Hungary (Balaton).
The only exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when we had the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia, and then the Yugoslav regime turned to the West, which led to significant restrictions on Czech tourists' travel to Yugoslavia.
A big paradox of the socialist period was that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. and Czechoslovakia) were not allowed to travel individually to socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel alone, for example to the Soviet Union or Poland, an invitation letter from that country was required; otherwise, individual travel was impossible.
At the time, travel agencies offered tours to the West, but you had to either stand in line all night with a sleeping bag or have "good friends" at the agency.
And that's not all.
A currency permit was required for travel to the West, and was not issued to politically unreliable people who were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not freely convertible; without a currency permit it was impossible to obtain money (western currency) for travel to the West.
Most often, Czechs spent their holidays at home, which led to the emergence of a large number of cottages and summer houses, this habit is still present today.
After 1989, tourism in the Czech Republic thus experienced a real revolution.
While before 1989 a vacation to the GDR or Bulgaria was the highlight of our travels, last year Czechs spent 4.5 million vacations in countries around the world.
The great paradox that we no longer realize is that before 1989, we could not freely visit Croatia, which is the most popular country today, because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
In the early 1990s, the visa requirement for Western Europe's neighbouring countries was abolished, leading to a huge wave of short trips, mainly to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks couldn't get enough of traveling to the West.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists slept in tents in parks because their income at the time was not enough to pay for a hotel or boarding house.
A typical feature of Czech tourism in that period was the desire to bring their own food (cans, salami, etc.) to save money.
Another important point is the introduction of the freely convertible Czech krona, which after decades our tourists can finally freely buy Western currency.
Our living standards and average incomes were rising, which led to another important development around 1997.
Since 1997, increased demand has allowed travel agencies to prepare regular flights operated by charter airlines, and now, in comparison to the past, air travel has become incredibly cheap due to the ability to order wholesale discounts.
By the late 1990s, Czechs didn't need visas to visit almost all the developed countries in the world except the United States, which made our travel even easier.
The next significant event in the history of travel after the revolution occurred in 2000 when the great demand led to the historic first direct charter flight from the Czech Republic to the exotic country, Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights have been taking Czech tourists to warm exotic countries.
Today, about 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries each year!
And another important event of this period, which symbolizes our development after the revolution, happened in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States abolished the visa requirement for Czech tourists, joining the ranks of the most developed countries in the world.
For the first time in history, Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad in 2008 (50.3%); and for the first time in history, they spent more than 15 thousand crowns per person during their holiday abroad, including their expenses at the destination.
