The Austrian Pavilion, designed by Karl Schwanzer for the 1958 World Exhibition in Brussels, is a famous example of modern post-war architecture with its simple forms, glass halls, and bold beliefs in technical progress.
The Schwanzer Pavilion won the Grand Prix of Architecture in 1958 for its lightweight steel and glass floating structure.
