He eventually became world famous in 1973 for his legendary four-cylinder BMW tower and its sister, the bowl-shaped building.
The pavilion, conceived as a building for temporary exhibitions, was moved to the Swiss Garden near Vienna South Station, converted and opened as the Museum of the 20th Century in 1962 - and is often referred to as the "House of the 20th Century" for this reason.
However, the building was not suitable for a museum for technical and spatial reasons - it had no walls on which to hang artworks and poor air conditioning.
However, it continued to be used until modern art in Vienna found a new home.
The house has been vacant since 2001 and its condition has been getting worse and worse.
Architect Adolph Krišanić has now restored the pavilion, which has been named "House of the 21st Century" and will be used as a museum of contemporary art.
