Smart crows filling cities
The crow is considered a problem bird in many places, and experts now say that it is impossible to drive these highly intelligent birds out of the cities.
Some people love birds, others would like to get rid of them as quickly as possible. Crows have been part of the urban landscape for centuries, but residents complaining of dirt and noise are increasing in many settlements.
The solution to the problem of birds, however, is far from being reached.
At the first crow symposium in Ler, East Frisia, experts argued that it was no longer possible to drive the crows out of the cities.
Experts from all over Germany discussed possible solutions.
Looking for alternatives in cities
Conservationists argued that the root of the problem in cities was the migration of highly protected crickets, pointing out that the use of chemicals in agriculture was increasingly destroying traditional habitats.
Hunting, building, and cutting down traditional trees for nesting made life difficult for the birds.
The crows are under guard.
In the city of Zest in Westphalia and in the northwest at Yever, Dipholz, Achim near Bremen and Ler there are large colonies with over 600 parent pairs.
The controversial project to shoot crows in Leer caused unfavourable headlines in 2005.
Critics described the trapping of birds and the beating of them with sticks as particularly cruel.
"The usual movement and intimidation is useless", said architect and landscape designer Werner Klever of Ler.
Destroying nests with water or cutting down trees often has unintended consequences, said environmentalist Manfred Kaiser of Larr, Baden-Württemberg.
"The animals disperse, and the large colonies divide and spread to other areas".
In addition, the scare may only be used in exceptional circumstances near hospitals, nursing homes and schools.
"We're gonna have to live with them.
The problem of cities is not solved by being isolated from the surrounding areas, says Lera Mayor Wolfgang Kellner.
A combination of scaring birds away from areas in need of protection and encouraging them to return to other areas could be a solution.
"Information stands instead of gasoline drums" was the slogan proposed by psychologist and ethnologist Uta Maria Jurgens, who advocates a completely different approach to birds. "We need to be confident in order to live with this problem".
Juergens was one of the founders of the educational crow route in Acherberg in Schleswig-Holstein, where information stands provide information about the lives of very intelligent crows.
The project is already attracting tourists.
Jurgens also expressed her opinion about complaints about noise made by birds: "Noise conveys a lot of information.
The birds' intelligence and cunning have become legendary, and the birds often use tools to grab a piece of meat, but they also make their own.
Behavioral researchers at Cambridge University recently tested the measurement of a bird's brain on four bats.
In one experiment, the birds quickly learned that they had to knock on the board to get the moth.
Without any special training, they learned the size and shape of the stone needed to knock down the plank.
In another experiment, the intelligent bats had to solve a more difficult problem.
The researchers placed a small bucket of moth larvae in a vertical cylinder.
The birds couldn't get to the prey with their beaks.
But the researchers gave them pieces of wire.
All four birds used the wire to make hooks and used the hooks to attach the bucket to the handle and pull it out of the cylinder.
Three of the four grasshoppers did it on the first try.
