Mass Murder - The Human Dimension
Peter Englund's tense and very kind new book, Beauty and Sorrow: A Personal History of World War I, begins with a long list of characters that makes your heart go cold.
Here's a tip for further reading: Carefully cut out this page and use it as a bookmark.
You'll get to know these people very closely as Mr. Englund tells the story, and this list of people will be your GPS, your beacon in those moments when, like one of these men and women, you stray off the road and get lost in the fog of war.
Mr. Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
The book he's writing now is unusual, he describes it, quite accurately, as "a work on anti-history".
There are few famous names, important treaties, or famous battles; there are almost no ambassadors, clever journalists, or discussions of tactics and military equipment.
It is not so much a book about what happened", he explains, "but a book about what it was like". It is about "feelings, impressions, experiences, and moods".
Beauty and Sorrow weaves together the experiences of 20 years of war, of more or less unremarkable men and women, on both sides of the front lines, from schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and employees.
Some of these people will be heroes.
Someone will be captured, lose an arm or a leg, go crazy or die.
Their lives flash here like church candles: new ones are added to the many others, and some are extinguished in the process.
Mr. Englund's book is a departure from the standard of historical books.
It's also a correction to the notion that World War I was just a hard trench war on the Western Front.
"Beauty and Sorrow" skillfully gives a panorama of other theaters of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
The soldiers in this book are being attacked by bees; one of them is celebrating Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; the unresolved problem is the tsetse flies.
It's an exciting book, almost from the beginning.
War is covering these people's lives like a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina smelling like smokeless gunpowder.
When you're a woman and you're at home with your kids and you hear a cannonade, will you stay put or run?
Who's coming, anyway?
Almost no one understands what's going on or why we should be fighting this war.
"The lack of facts", notes Mr. Englund, "is filled with speculation, speculation, hope, fear, obsession, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors".
"Beauty and Sorrow" follows the lives of Florence Farmboro, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor in the German High Seas Fleet.
Their stories are mostly taken from memoirs, letters and other material that has already been published.
The stories of their lives may be scary or exciting, but they are extremely vivid thanks to the small moments and fragmentary details collected by Mr. Englund.
Many of them are about deprivation and how to cope.
He tells the story of a German schoolgirl, and he says, "Erzaz, erzaz everywhere".
"Replacement coffee, fake aluminum, fake rubber, paper bandages, wooden buttons" is what they say.
He keeps talking about the Erzsá food in Germany.
He describes "meat of pressed rice cooked in lamb fat (and decorated with a fake bone made of wood); tobacco made of dried roots and dried potato peel; shoes struck with wood".
He notes that there were "837 registered meat substitutes allowed in the production of sausage, 511 registered coffee substitutes".
Some stories are about honor and courage.
One American man, who recognizes his own urge for cruelty, says of war: "You feel that, after all, that is what men were made for, not to sit in comfortable chairs with a cigarette and whiskey and a nightly newspaper or a best-seller and claim that this display is civilization and that there is no barbarian under your starched shirt with the cuffs".
The British soldier, on the other hand, notices that he will most likely die and no one will notice or feel bad.
"When you accept the idea of self-sacrifice, you want to think that it will be in public", he writes.
But it's the opposite, it's like a convict being hanged in secret.
Other comments concern the old Europe that is falling apart and new forms of fear.
"Conflict was increasingly becoming an economic competition", writes Mr. Englund, "a war of factories".
He notes the arrival of what he calls "a new species in the bestiary of the new century: a beautifully expressive and ideologically convinced mass murderer in a well-sewn suit who carries out a massacre at his desk".
People act in unexpected ways: lowly acts are as much as heroism.
Mr. Englund told of soldiers who tried everything to catch a venereal disease from prostitutes to avoid serving on the front.
"The most grotesque expression of this is the trade in the gonorrheal pus that soldiers bought and smeared on their genitals in the hope of getting into the hospital", he writes.
"The desperate rubbed his eyes, often leading to blindness for life".
Translated from the Swedish by Peter Graves, Mr. Englund's prose is flexible but unpretentious, perfectly suited to his humanistic task.
In dozens of small scenes, he shows how the war "unleashed forces beyond our control: extreme nationalism, social revolution, religious hatred".
People are starting to ask why their leaders are making them go to war.
The best books about World War I were often indirect, like Paul Fassel's The Great War and Modern Memory or novels like Erich Maria Remarque's On the Western Front Without Change, rather than exhaustive historical works.
Mr. Englund's book is part of this unorthodox pantheon.
His book has the most amazing ending I can remember in nonfiction.
I'm not gonna tell you.
But it's like he reached out from a book to a page with a list of characters, snatched it from your hand and lit it with a match.
