Walls have eyes: How researchers study you on Facebook
Before he became the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was a regular guy who posted his anti-immigration views online.
Breivik, who confessed to the mass murder in Norway in July that killed 77 people, appeared in his first public court hearing on Monday.
While Breivik may have acted alone, he was far from alone online: he spent a lot of time preparing for the attack behind his computer, interacting with millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social media.
After the summer tragedy, researchers wanted to know more about these people.
But how do we find them?
It's easy, you just have to go on Facebook.
"We found that it was easy to get to them", says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recent report on European cyberpopulism by the UK's DEMOS research centre.
The stock of personal data on Facebook is so large, Bartlett says, that researchers could easily use the site's advertising tool to target the right demographic with scientific accuracy - something marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million right-wing groups across Europe and then put out an advert for them, but instead of showing a new group or a diet product, the ad asked the user to take a survey that asked questions about their education level, attitudes toward violence and optimism about their own future.
Using Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to survey more than 10,000 participants from 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - even without leaving their offices.
"This is a whole new way of doing research", says Bartlett.
Some of the results are not as surprising: online supporters of right-wing groups are mostly young men who are unhappy with immigration.
But surprisingly, "those who combine their online and offline activities are more intelligent, more democratic, and less aggressive than those who hide behind their monitors".
DEMOS' work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a popular new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to learn about everything from health issues to social trends expressed in likes, wall posts and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three posts a day, Facebook's "super-reality" is driving a research boom, increasing the number of scientific articles with the site's title in the title by 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it allows them to study people who they couldn't reach on the street with a notebook.
"Before, if you wanted to interview people from the British National Party, it would be very difficult to identify them".
"You would have to join the party and they would never accept you", says Bartlett.
"Facebook excludes all of that - you're talking to them directly".
Others say that the site could be used to identify and research social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues found that college students who discussed their drunken exploits on Facebook were significantly more likely to become alcoholic than students who kept quiet about it.
Moreno suggests that students' peers, such as their dorm mentors, could monitor the site and intervene to help a student who updates drunk statuses too often.
"You can't solve a problem without identifying it", said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Moreno and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior, and Development at the Children's Research Institute of Seattle.
"We found a way to identify at-risk children who would otherwise be undetected".
Facebook also constantly extracts all kinds of data about its users.
The site's data-processing team processed statistics on relationship status and Valentine's Day, voter turnout in the 2010 midterm elections, as well as the National Happiness Index (mostly using information only they have access to - champions of cyber freedom have long insisted that the site should make its vast data collection publicly available for research).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them whether they like it or not -- in exchange for being able to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, the site can process your personal data.
But what if Facebook users are taking part in a study they don't even know about?
While researchers have strict rules for doing offline research, online data is publicly available.
"I don't think many users even think about the possibility of a researcher monitoring their profiles", says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, about a study he conducted in 2006 using publicly accessible student Facebook pages.
"As far as they knew, it was just between them and their friends".
So there's a question of methodology.
Even offline, there's no guarantee that the subject is completely honest.
On Facebook, it's impossible to know how much of the information on a user's profile and page is true.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do off Facebook are two completely different things", Selwyn says.
That's why, despite years of technology research, Selvin thinks that a notebook and a pen are still the best research tools you can use.
"There is no substitute for going out into the real world and talking to real people", he says.
"Social research is supposed to be about social, and most social still happens offline".
