7 lessons from the lost Steve Jobs interview that's playing in the theater this week
After Steve Jobs died on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford, describing the tech genius as the Great Inventor of Modernity.
But what Apple fans may find the biggest revelation in a recently re-discovered interview, which was recalled ahead of the previews in major markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood about business processes and manufacturing technologies.
He was, of course, a designer, a dreamer and considered himself a hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and modernization of production processes who believed that many business leaders suffered from "the sickness of thinking that a really great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] a great idea is separated from a great product by a huge amount of skilled labor".
Back in 1995, Bob Kringley was creating a TV series called Triumph of the Nerds about the advent of the personal computer, and he spent over an hour with Jobs in a unique, long conversation.
By that time, it had been about 10 years since Jobs was fired from Apple, and he was already working at his new computer company NeXT, waiting for the Internet to be mass-produced.
While a small portion of the Kringley interview was used in the Nerds, he says the originals of the interview were lost in transport.
It wasn't until after Jobs' death that a complete VHS copy was found in the director's garage.
This footage, slightly edited, became the basis for the 68-minute film Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which opens at Landmark Theaters this Wednesday and Thursday.
For a man known for his hatred of detailed interviews, Jobs seems unusually willing to lay out his technological philosophy and business strategy.
And incredibly thoughtful.
At four different points during the interview, there are long gaps between questions and answers -- 10-15 seconds of reflection, where Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts to be more precise.
There are also moments when Jobs' perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems irritated by the questions of Kringley, causing him to move quickly to more important issues or phenomena.
In this pre-Pixar, iPod, and iPhone-era Lost interview, there's something ominously prophetic about how Jobs evaluates what he sees different companies doing right and wrong, and offers his own vision for the future of information technology.
It's one thing to read about the posthumous reviews of Jobs' work, but there's something vulnerable and inspiring about Jobs, who we see here, a restless dreamer on the verge of greatness.
He has a vision of what things could and should be.
Soon after he said everything here, he went and did it.
A little summary of the seven significant findings of the Lost Interview:
About how he learned to run a business:
"All my time in business, I've been asking, "Why do you do this?" and the answers you always get are, "Oh, that's just how it's done".
No one knows why they do what they do, no one thinks business very deeply.
Here's what I found out.
Jobs goes on to describe in detail his attempts to streamline reporting at Apple.
Frustrated by the way the cost records often started with "standard expenses" that were taken from the ceiling and then adjusted with "specification", he created an automated structure that ensured they could track business expenses down to the smallest detail.
About the Pope joke:
Jobs goes into great detail about the "blue box" he designed with Steve Wozniak, a device that allowed people to effectively hack into a phone company and make long-distance calls for free.
The device has been written about before, but Jobs' euphoria here in describing the blue box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
He tells how he and Wozniak tested the box using a pay phone, ordering a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another until they connected as many stations as possible.
"We've been around the globe half a dozen times, and you're yelling at a pay phone, and it's coming in a minute later at the next pay phone", Jobs says with a smile.
"We were young, and all we learned was that we could engineer something that could control billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world".
We both knew a little bit, but we could engineer a little thing that could control a big thing -- it was an incredible lesson, and I don't think Apple could ever have come about without that.
Jobs goes on to describe one famous stunt that he and Wozniak almost pulled off, calling the Vatican through a blue box at midnight and asking the Pope to take the phone, trying to copy Henry Kissinger.
When various members of the Catholic hierarchy were called in the middle of the night to speak with the American diplomat, the two burst out laughing just before the Pope himself was raised to answer the phone.
About being in love with technology (and Bill Hewlett's cold calling):
At the age of 12, while hunting for spare parts to assemble a frequency meter, he found Bill Hewlett in the phone book and called him.
Shortly after their 20-minute phone conversation, Jobs got a summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"It had a big impact on me, it was the only company I saw at that age, and it shaped my view of what a company is and how well they treat their employees".
Jobs later became one of the HP employees who visited the company's research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw "the very first desktop computer".
It was the size of a suitcase, and it had a little monitor with a beam tube, and I fell in love with it.
I used to go to HP a lot as a teenager and I used to go around that machine and write programs for it.
About the improvised innovation:
