Scalia and Thomas have lunch with health care opponents while the court is in session.
On the day the Supreme Court convened behind closed doors to discuss the politically contentious issue of whether to hear President Obama's health care law challenge, two of its justices, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, were honored at a luncheon sponsored by the law firm that will be challenging the case before the Supreme Court.
This case occurred last Thursday when all nine judges met to discuss the petition.
One of the items on the agenda was a petition backed by 26 states challenging a sweeping health care overhaul passed by Congress last year, a law that brought together conservative activists from across the nation.
The judges agreed to review the case; in fact, a 5 1/2 hour turnaround is expected in March 2012, and the outcome is likely to be a setback for the presidential race, which will be in full swing by the time the court ruling is announced.
The lawyer who will stand before the court and argue that the health care law should be repealed is likely to be Paul Clement, who was deputy attorney general under George W. Bush.
Clement's law firm, Bancroft PLLC, was one of nearly two dozen firms that helped sponsor the annual luncheon of the Federalist Society, a long-standing group that consistently advocates conservative legal principles.
Another firm that sponsored the lunch represents one of the trade associations that challenged the law, the National Federation of Independent Business.
Another sponsor was pharmaceutical giant Pflizer Inc, which has a huge financial stake in the outcome of the lawsuit.
The luncheon was held at the Washington Hotel a few hours after the court hearing.
Among those present was Mitch McConnell, the Senate Republican leader and a known opponent of the health care law.
The guests of honor at the dinner?
Nothing new: two judges have been attending Federalist Society events for years.
And that's not against ethics at all.
In fact, judges are exempt from the Code of Conduct, which governs the actions of lower federal judges.
If they did, they might fall under Principle 4C of the code, which states, "A judge may attend charitable events of legal and other organizations, although a judge may not be a speaker, guest of honor, or be mentioned in the program of such events".
However, the apparent proximity of Scalia and Thomas to the two law firms in this case, as well as to a company with large financial interests, was a sufficient signal to ethic activists in the government.
"This staggering violation of ethics and disregard for the code contradicts claims by some judges that the court remains faithful to the same rules that apply to all other federal judges", said Bob Edgar, president of the Common Pleas.
"Judges were drinking and dining at a formal fundraiser with lawyers whose cases are now in court".
Their appearance and assistance in raising money for this event undermines all claims of impartiality and is unacceptable.
Scalia and Thomas hardly pay attention to critics who say they are quite willing to mix court cases with the cases of groups like the Federalist Society.
And Thomas's wife, Jeannie, is a well-known conservative activist.
Moreover, conservatives argue that it is the ethical question that arises with respect to Judge Elena Kagan, not Scalia and Thomas.
Kagan was the chief legal officer in the Obama administration when the first legal challenges to the law were filed at the trial court level.
Her critics demanded that Kagan refuse to hear the case because she was too involved in defending the law then to be impartial now.
Kagan didn't show any sign of what she was going to do.
