ADB urges Asia to help save the eurozone
The Asian Development Bank has committed India and China to be ready to help save the eurozone from the European debt crisis to avoid a long-term recession that would halt Asian economic growth.
Rajat Nag, managing director of the ADB's Manila office, said the two fastest-growing major economies should "do everything they can" to accelerate the currency bloc's recovery through either the International Monetary Fund or direct bilateral agreements.
He warned that the BRICS countries were looking at Europe's difficulties "impartially", and said that Asian financial assistance alongside European leadership and resources could help avoid a long-term downturn in the global economy.
"This is about all of us".
"So anyone who can help Europe get out of the crisis is useful", he told the Financial Times in an interview at the World Economic Forum in Mumbai.
"Asia may be somewhat protected, but it cannot be invulnerable".
"So if China and India can help, they should".
The European Monetary Union has been severely undermined by the European debt crisis in recent months.
In recent days, Italy's borrowing has risen alarmingly, and the prime ministers of both Italy and Greece have resigned.
The unfolding debt crisis in Europe has raised fears that it could push the world economy back into recession, and has led to calls for the leading emerging economies to come together to help the eurozone find a solution.
Mr. Nag predicted that any Asian aid would be through the IMF, but said that bilateral cooperation -- like buying EU bailout bonds, a means to ensure financial stability in Europe -- gives a huge bargaining power to Europe's Asian partners.
Anand Sharma, India's commerce minister, said that "India will do everything it can" to help the eurozone as its own economy is now experiencing a decline in exports and a decline in foreign investment.
"Nobody wants the eurozone to remain unstable and unrestful", he said.
"We have a huge challenge and we need to maintain high growth rates".
"It's not an option, it's a requirement, because that's where we're going to get jobs for tens of millions of our boys and girls".
Others argue that there is no point for emerging economies like India to help rich Europeans when they face their own deep economic problems.
Ashutosh Varshni, a professor at Brown University in the US, said it would be very difficult from a political point of view to provide aid to Europe for India's 1.2 billion people, of whom about 800 million live on $2 a day or less.
"At some point they will find out that Greeks retire at 50 and go to the seaside for holidays, and it will not be well received", he said.
Lee Howell, managing director of the World Economic Forum, also wondered why India's reserves should be used to keep Greek large and well-paid public sector workers working in poorly organized, unprofitable enterprises such as railways.
Mr Nag said the eurozone crisis threatened "significant direct consequences" across Asia.
The ADB's forecast for 7.5 percent growth in Asia in 2011/12 is now facing "downside risks" due to the threat from Europe.
He said vulnerable emerging markets need to make "emergency plans" to protect themselves from recessions and significant capital outflows from their economies.
The Pentagon 's dire warnings about potential defense spending cuts .
Defense Secretary Leon Panetta heated up the situation Monday in Congress, warning that expected automatic budget cuts would undermine national security and trigger a financial chain reaction from the Pentagon's corridors to the battlefields of Afghanistan on the line and to the civilian assembly.
The Pentagon is already getting used to a $450 billion cut in the coming decade, but now fears that additional cuts of $600 billion or more may be inevitable if Congress cannot agree on spending.
"The consequences of these cuts will be devastating to the department", Panetta said in a letter to Republican Senators John McCain of Arizona and Lindsey Graham of South Carolina.
He said that the failure of Congress to pass a budget agreement and the resulting so-called sequestration would trigger a 23% overall cut and shut down many new projects.
"Such a drastic cut, applied so thoughtlessly, would make most of our shipbuilding and construction projects unworkable - you cannot buy three-quarters of a ship or building - and would seriously damage other modernization efforts", Panetta wrote to the senators.
"We will also have to lay off many of our full-time employees, and since the reduction will be made so quickly, we will almost certainly have to lay off full-time employees to achieve our goal".
"These changes will undermine the confidence of those who support our military and seriously damage our readiness".
The cuts will ultimately affect the military, Panetta said.
"While the military funding of foreign emergency operations is not directly affected by the sequester, military gains will be severely affected by a major disruption in the main budgets", Panetta warned.
"Contract personnel will be cut, which will end up cancelling the contracts and the surveillance agreement that supports the troops".
"Personnel will be cut, which will delay payments to military suppliers, and legal and political support will be disrupted".
Two senators wrote to Panetta 10 days ago, requesting details of the possible consequences of automatic cuts at the Department of Defense.
"The result of the sequester at the Department of Defense will be the rapid decline of the United States as the world's leading military power".
"We stand firm against these draconian actions", the senators said in a joint statement Monday night when they released Panetta's letter.
"It's not a solution we can live with, and it's not a solution we should force on ourselves".
"Sequestration is a threat to the national security interests of the United States, and it cannot be allowed to happen".
Whether Panetta's letter or the senators' latest warnings lead to a budget compromise or reinforce calls to exempt the Pentagon from cuts, we'll see later.
Panetta was completely honest about the potential cuts, even though he came to the Pentagon after years of budgeting in Congress and the White House and realizing he was facing a tough choice.
At a press conference last week, the Secretary of Defense painted a bleak picture of what could happen next -- shell-based but no-nuclear forces.
"It's a ship without sailors".
"This is a team without bullets".
"It's a wing of an airplane without adequate training".
"It's a paper tiger, an army with barracks, buildings and bombs without adequately trained soldiers capable of carrying out the mission", Panetta said in his opening remarks at the Pentagon.
"It is a force that suffers from an unstable fighting spirit, poor preparedness and inability to fight potential enemies".
"It's actually encouraging aggression".
In an appendix to his letters to McCain and Graham Panetta, he voiced new details of how the cuts "generate significant operational risks: slow down the response to crises, conflicts and disasters; severely limit our ability to be first to deploy and respond anywhere in the world; and lead to unacceptable risk in future combat operations".
And Panetta said that some of the biggest defense projects could face obstacles, including those that have already passed testing, and some that are only in the early planning stages.
This list includes the F35 single-seat fighter, a planned new bomber, a new-generation ballistic submarine, a new coastal zone warship, and a new ground combat vehicle that the Army and Marines need to replace the Hummer.
Stopping further development and testing of the F35 could save $80 billion over 10 years, but its proponents say it is a vital next step to improve and counter potential threats from China and other adversaries.
How to catch a liar
A quick glance at the latest headlines shows just how serious and pervasive deception and lying are in our daily lives.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy contesting sexual harassment allegations from multiple women; each side accuses the other of lying.
The University of Pennsylvania administration has been charged with perjury for allegedly concealing that a retired football coach molested boys.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught speaking to US President Barack Obama over a microphone that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
Lying destroys careers and shakes up nations.
New York congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself by denying his pranks, which were quickly refuted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign finance fraud related to the cover-up of extramarital affairs.
And again, no one alive at the time will ever forget the media circus of President Bill Clinton being caught lying about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky during his second term in office.
Stories of cheating on school and college exams are common.
There were instances when teachers gave students answers to tests so that they could evaluate their performance.
The teachers who are supposed to teach the opposite are sending the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How many lies do we face?
Studies show that you lie an average of 10 to 200 times a day.
Now it's assumed that a significant portion of this is a lie to save face.
Another study found that strangers lie an average of three times in the first 10 minutes of meeting.
Lying detection or detection is a skill that everyone needs for both personal and professional purposes.
Unlike the room game of, say, charades where you have to shout, "I've got you!" lie detection is a serious area of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities engaged in comprehensive research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One result of the study is that most of the old myths about lying have been debunked.
Liars look you in the eye.
They don't always stutter, stutter, blush, or fuss.
This does not mean that lying is hard to spot or unmask.
An experienced liar can get to the truth by observing the structure of statements, facial expressions, question structure, and time characteristics.
I've spent several years researching scientific discoveries in a vast and ever-growing segment of knowledge about lying, and it's clear that lie detection is a modern skill that's easy to learn and that helps you navigate our complex world -- especially if your professional responsibilities include recruiting, interviewing, negotiating, or management.
Good liars are excellent at reading others, making them feel relaxed, managing their own emotions, and intuitively sensing how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men lie more about themselves than women do about others, usually to protect someone's feelings, that married people lie less to their partners than single people do (but the lies they tell are usually the most outrageous).
We also know that if you're perceived as a cheater, others will feel less guilty about cheating on you.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your subject.
It's called "state definition".
This helps provide a starting point for evaluating changes further.
Watch the posture, the laughter, the voice characteristics of your subject.
You'd better know if the person is regularly tapping his feet in a normal state, so you don't make unfair accusations when you see a tapping in the middle of a meeting.
Then look for groups of deceitful verbal and nonverbal actions.
Treat these groups as red flags, not proof of deception.
Liars can focus on their upper body when they're trying to remember their story, they can put their feet toward the door, they can lean toward the exit, they can change their posture in a certain way, or they can show "relief after the interview" -- that exaggerated sigh of relief and change of posture when all the hard questions are behind them.
Investigators often fake the end of interrogation signal just to look at that relief after the interview.
So, pay attention to the speech of your subject.
Scott Peterson is known to have tripped and used the past tense to claim that his murdered wife was alive, leading to a nationwide manhunt.
Pushing people may also use distance in speech, such as "I did not have sexual relations with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeating a difficult question in full.
The most typical verbal indicators are barely noticeable.
Someone might use "qualification language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... actually... as far as I know... as far as I know".
This makes the response more emotional than actual, and is often a red flag.
There is no magic bullet to detect lies, but you can master the skill of detecting deception.
These skills will increase the chances of anyone avoiding being a victim of skilled scammers in their professional and personal lives.
