Climate problems have slowed the economy
During the first year of Mario Lopez's rule, Sinaloa's unemployment and illegal labor market increased, foreign funding decreased, and the economy was weakened.
2011 is the year that will go down in Sinaloa's economic history as the first year of the government of Mario Lopez Valdés, also called the year of change, which raised great hopes for economic development, but given the unfavorable climatic conditions at the beginning of the year, there was no growth, however, there was a decline in the main indicators of economic development.
The February cold temperatures not only cost the agricultural sector millions, but they also limited the growth opportunities of the state economy, causing economic activity to decline by 3.6 percent overall in the first half of the year, mainly due to a historic 31.16 percent drop in agriculture, which affected the dynamics of other sectors of the economy.
According to a report on the areas affected by the frost provided by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, 835,582 hectares were affected, of which 78.03 percent were affected in whole and the remaining 21.07 percent were partially affected.
The decline in economic activity caused, until November, a steady increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, during the first three quarters there was an accelerated increase in the unemployment rate, from January to March 55,053 Sinaloa residents were unemployed, with a share of 4.53 percent of the economically active population, in the second quarter the share increased to 5.28 percent, and from July to September it continued to grow to 6.19 percent, a share that in terms of the number of people is more than 74,000 Sinaloa unemployed residents, which is 18.969 people more compared to the first half.
Liquidity decline
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year has been driven by many factors, for economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences at the Autonomous University (UAS), the rise in unemployment can be explained indirectly, by actions that were taken in public policy.
"What we are seeing now is an increase in unemployment that is linked to several factors, including a loss of liquidity in the market to limit resources imposed by a law that was passed in Congress to fight money laundering, because people who illegally own dollars are not easy to work with, invest and use for anything", he said.
Stopped immigration
Lopez Cervantes said that there is also a demographic factor in the rise in unemployment.
"The number of people who leave the state to look for work abroad in the U.S. has been limited, firstly because of the difficulty of entry, and secondly because once they enter, they already face a lot of difficulties in finding work, so a group of people stay and demand jobs here in the state, and as a result, the unemployment rate is rising", he said.
Violation of formal requirements
Sinaloa's labour market analysis is made worse when one considers the high number of violations that are prevalent in the working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 percent of the active population of the state works without being mentioned as workers in any social protection institution.
In addition to unemployment and irregularities in registration, another reminder of working in the state is low wages; the state has the lowest salaries in the country, according to records from the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Ministry of Labor and Social Welfare.
The average monthly income of Sinaloa workers was 5,352 pesos until September, far below the national average of 7,375 pesos.
Reducing FDI
In addition to the decline in economic activity and high unemployment, 2011 saw the largest outflow of foreign direct investment in the past 10 years, according to the Treasury Department, with January-July FDI totaling $630,697, showing a 87.74 percent drop from $5,143,312 during the same period last year.
For its part, the state government's Ministry of Economic Development recorded only 17,280,000 pesos of investment during the year, which was mainly in the service sector.
The debt
Amid the economic downturn, the state government requested approval of a 3 billion peso loan in July during the state congress to be used to invest in infrastructure projects in 18 municipalities to revive the economy, only 2.600 million pesos were approved locally, and no debt benefits were expected in any sector of the state economy until November.
Reactions
For business people, the first year of the Mario Lopez Valdes government demonstrates the government's lack of capacity.
Miguel Loredo Lopez, president of the National Chamber of Manufacturing, said that during 2011 there was a lack of coordination among various sectors, including the state government itself.
"The economic efficiency in Sinaloa this year has been really low, we have to work hard to regain the positions lost this year, in 2012 we have to double our efforts, we have not been able to coordinate the efforts of everyone and above all, the good and synchronized work of the new government team, we hope that next year will be much better", he said.
The slowdown in the economy
Lopez Loredo said events such as early freezes have brought the state's economy to a halt this year and limited its efficiency and growth.
"The low volumes of the economy are the result of several events, including frost, one of the main effects was a slow economy that is not getting fast enough to create an economic dynamic that allows us to have an acceptable level of processes, goods and services and therefore at the end of the year we close it below our expectations", he said.
Revisiting the direction
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederation of Employers of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, said the state needed to continue its most dynamic manufacturing activity.
"In general, we found that we worked on this, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program that will redefine the direction and economic course of the state, it is necessary to mobilize all the material and human resources that Sinaloa has", he said.
The work ahead
President Coparmex stressed the importance of defining the future direction to better direct the government's efforts.
"In general, I would say that the Government is trying to be successful in various areas, in terms of economic development there is little progress, but it is important to develop a long-term program", he said.
He noted that the current administration has demonstrated progress in its own way of conducting public policy.
"There are facts that allow us to say that the government is starting to get involved and that I can say that some work has been done and I think the government is aware that there is still a lot to do", he said.
