Court approves "digital television transition" in Mexico in 2015
The switch from analog to digital is one of the most important changes the world has seen in recent years.
The Supreme Court (Supreme Court) has rejected constitutional claims brought by the Senate and House of Representatives against a presidential decree that postpones the so-called "transition to digital television" from 2021 to 2015 because it did not collect the eight votes needed to overturn it.
A minority of four ministers, including the court's president, Juan Silva Mesa, felt that President Felipe Calderon had not exceeded his authority by issuing a decree detailing the actions to move to digital terrestrial television.
As a result, the constitutional claims made by the Senate were rejected due to the lack of the qualified majority of eight votes required for the court to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and it remains in force.
The draft statement, prepared by Minister Olga Sanchez Cordero, proposed declaring the decree unconstitutional because the regulation of radio and television programming is a right vested in the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel) by law, in violation of the principles of hierarchical subordination and legislative reserve.
Only Salvidar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sanchez Cordero voted for the project.
On this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies held two constitutional debates to refute the decree and support the complaints, Minister Sanchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all actions mentioned in it regarding the transition to digital broadcasting.
At the meeting of ministers it was also decided to reject the request of the Chamber of Deputies without entering into the discussion of the project, also under the responsibility of Minister Sanchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister said that he did not agree with the arguments of the project in the sense that the federal executive cannot determine by general rules the measures to which the state administration should prepare.
"I also don't think that if it did happen, it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body", and reminded that planning public policy in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is relevant to the federal executive, which has a constitutional mandate to govern the state.
The replacement of analogue signals with digital ones is one of the most important changes that has occurred in recent years, leading to better use of the radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
Delaying the transition, he said, would mean delaying the benefits of the digital transformation, which includes meeting societal needs that have more than just a technical dimension, "since it covers economic, social, political and national security issues".
These issues, he said, "require the work of the entire system, formed on the principle of state economic management, includes a group of authorities that the Constitution unites into the state executive power".
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the transition to digital broadcasting, and have done so with the help of the executive, despite the presence of highly specialized technical institutions.
It cannot be concluded that the government, by passing the decree under discussion, which in any case affects the competence of Congress, ensures in the administrative sphere compliance with the laws passed by the Legislative Assembly, he said.
In Michoacan, they're analyzing the possibility of a voice-by-voice count.
According to the data provided to the PPRV, the difference between first and second place in the gubernatorial election is only 27 percent, even without counting the 879 votes in the 6,074 minutes.
The possibility of counting "vote for vote" is real for this year's election process in Michoacán, where, according to the preliminary results program (PREP), the difference between first and second place in the gubernatorial election is only 27 percent, even without counting the 879 votes in the 6,074 minutes.
In this light, the chair of the General Council of the Michoacan Elections Institute (IEM), Maria de Los Angeles Llanderal Saragossa, recalled that a few days ago, on November 9, the electoral body approved a package of principles to harmonize local rules with the federal electoral reform.
It should be recalled that Michoacan did not adopt the Constitution or the State Electoral Code or the Voting Rights Act, as the state Congress approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for their entry into force in this electoral process and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel did not include its publication in the law in the State Gazette, stating that he had some objections.
On the same day, November 9, the Supreme Court of Justice (SJC) ruled on a constitutional claim brought by the local legislature and called the state representative's vote on constitutional reform "invalid and illegal" as he had no right to "allow or support them".
In an interview about the possibility of "vote by vote", Maria de los Ángeles Lianderal argued that with the adoption of appropriate principles by the General Council of the IWM, it would be possible to provide a partial or complete count of votes to the local electoral body.
For example, a partial recount of one or more ballot boxes may be made if the results of the voting records do not match; there is no ballot box or the ballot box is not in the chairman's possession; or there are obvious errors or corrections in the ballot box.
In addition, a total recount of votes in all ballot boxes may take place when there is evidence that the difference between the presumed winner of the election and the second-place vote is less than or equal to one percent, provided that there is a request from the party and/or coalition representative who put up the second of the candidates at the beginning of the session.
A total recount will also be carried out if at the end of the usual count it is established that the difference between the winner and the candidate who took second place is less than or equal to one percent, provided there is a request from the political party whose candidate took second place, in case the ballot boxes that were taken into account in the partial recount are excluded.
It is worth noting that this is the situation in the elections in Morelia, where, according to the PPRV, the difference between first and second place is only 0.16 percent, even if we do not count 129 votes out of the total of 923 in the protocol.
