The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday .
The new prime minister, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the president of Italy to present a new government that will face a crisis that has brought the country to the brink of economic catastrophe.
Italy's newly appointed prime minister, Mario Monti, will meet with the president on Wednesday to present a new government that will face a crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic disaster and damaged the entire eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace said that Monti, appointed on Sunday, would meet with the president, Giorgio Napolitano, on Wednesday to confirm he could form a government.
He is expected to present a cabinet composed mostly of technocrats, although it is unclear when the new executive branch will take office.
Monty said he would present the president with the results of his negotiations with the political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to reaffirm my full confidence in our country's ability to get out of this difficult period", the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monty did not say directly that he was able to form a government, but the tone of his comments showed that the obstacles had been overcome.
"The structure is well laid out now", he said.
Monty completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, which is much less than usual since Italy was struggling with a political and financial crisis that brought their debt to a critical level.
The administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve the austerity package demanded by European leaders to restore confidence in Italy.
Under pressure from Monti to hurry, volatile markets set the yield on Italy's 10-year BTP bonds at 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to be bailed out.
Emma Marchegalia, leader of the Italian Employers' Federation, told reporters after meeting with Monty: "We said we would actively support this government".
We believe this government is Italy's last chance to get out of this crisis.
Monti's chances of success were largely based on the support of the LDP party of Silvio Berlusconi, who was forced to resign on Saturday due to the crisis.
"We believe that Professor Monty's efforts should lead to a good outcome", Angelino Alfano, secretary of the center-right party, told reporters.
The support of the LDP, Italy's largest party, is important because so far many of its members have opposed the governmental majority of technocrats that Monti is forming.
Parliamentary support
The new Monty government must have strong parliamentary support to implement reforms that are likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blocking or suspension of these attempts could lead to a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks has stepped up pressure, warning that Monti's failure could be a disaster.
Monty began his consultations with political parties, unions and business groups, as well as youth and women's organizations on Monday.
He'll finish his series of meetings Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who allowed an extremely quick transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief pause at the end of last week when it became clear that Berlusconi would step down, Italy's debt value has now reached a critical level amid uncertainty over whether the new prime minister will be successful.
Bailing out Italy with a 1.8 billion euro national debt would be too much for modern eurozone financial protectors.
Monty said his government would last until the next election, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians would only give him time to reform before calling new elections.
Monty said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the main parties insist it should be made up of only technical experts, a testament to their dissatisfaction with the process being affected by the financial situation.
Political sources said that the mutual distrust and disagreement between the parties complicated the attempt to include political figures.
