The quintet is touring the country for their 20th anniversary .
A trip to Costa Rica is a dream come true.'
In an exclusive interview with Viva, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament said the band is ready to play one of their best shows next Sunday at the National Stadium.
It's been over 20 years of waiting, but the band says that for them it's also a dream come true to play in this country.
This was the claim of bassist and founder, Jeff Ament, who gave an exclusive interview to Viva from Brazil last week.
The band is on tour in South America to celebrate their 20th anniversary and will make their only stop in Central America on Sunday, the 20th.
They will perform at the National Stadium starting at 7:30 p.m. with Los Angeles-based The X and local band Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt from a conversation that is available online in full at The Nation.
For your Costa Rican fans, is it a dream come true that Pearl Jam will play in Costa Rica?
A trip to Costa Rica is a dream come true for us, too.
This is only our second visit to South and Central America, and so far, everything is going well.
I've only been to Costa Rica once - on vacation, it's a beautiful country, and I think we can stay there for a few days.
So we're very excited to bring our music there.
I ask because there's a certain loyalty to the band; the fans are living in tension in the days before the show.
What would you say to your most loyal fans?
Thank you for being with us all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica, thank you for waiting so long, and we regret it took us so long to get here.
Some people, waiting for your concert, are treating it like the biggest show of the year.
Does this add a little tension to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we've played in the last 21 years have been in the last two weeks.
We did some great shows in São Paulo and we hope that it's got us in shape for this gig in Costa Rica.
We really want to play here.
We love this country, we love surfing and jungle, and when it comes to those two things, Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you learn about Costa Rica and its surfing waves?
We have a lot of surfing friends, and I have a good friend who lives in Tamarindo, and the waves are amazing.
My friends always go surfing to Costa Rica and Nicaragua, and also to Mexico, which are great places to surf, and that's how we learned about it from people who love surfing.
Looking at the tour, you guys did a great show with a lot of songs.
What are your plans for the Costa Rica show?
Since we've never played there before, we have no limitations on what we can do.
We're going to try to do the best show we can with the most diverse songs; we're going to try to play a few songs from each album and present our fans with a wide variety of repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
How's that?
I think part of the reason is because we have nine records and we can play over 120 songs, and everybody likes different songs, so it's hard to pick which songs to play every night.
When we have two or three songs that we haven't played in a while, it keeps us tuned in and surprises us, because it reminds us of the reasons why we loved those songs and what we might have forgotten.
It makes the show more interesting for us and therefore, I think, makes it more interesting for people.
This tour marks 20 years of your career.
Looking back, is it hard to believe what you've done?
Yes, of course.
First of all, I think none of us ever imagined that we'd be in a rock band and the fact that we've been doing this for over 20 years makes it feel like a dream.
We're happy with our success and we're very excited that we can continue to make music together.
We all love each other and we all love making music.
We're happy to travel to places in the world we've always wanted to go.
It's going very well for us.
What does it mean to you to be a significant part of the grunge boom?
It's always been an honor to be part of this group of great collectives.
We're good friends with the guys from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It's great when a movement starts out as a group of friends, and that's unusual.
Occasionally, one group from one city appears, but it's much stranger when five or ten groups appear in the same city at the same time.
We're proud and honored to be part of a band from Seattle.
I still play with some of them now and then.
Last year we were at the festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on their tour, so we're happy to be friends with all of them and we're honored to be part of the Seattle sound that came out.
It's also very strange that a band like yours can stay together and in the same lineup for so long.
Yeah, the four of us have been together for 21 years, and Matt joined us 13 years ago, which is way longer than most bands.
First, I think we're lucky to be alive, and second, we care about others.
We're all very close friends, and because of that, we also opened up musical paths that give everyone the freedom to experiment.
We trust each other's music, and it couldn't be better.
Your attitude toward the word fame was not easy, but your success enabled you to do whatever you wanted.
How do you find the balance?
As we got older, it became easier to find balance.
We make sure that you don't stay on tour too long because it's easy to get into this game of big crowds and people who love your music.
As long as you remember that people are here for the music, it reminds you that you have to respect the music and what made it, not decide to be famous and be a rock star, something none of us really care about.
How do you remember your other project, Manother Love Bone?
I think we write really good songs and it was great at first.
We were a band for almost three years and didn't release an album until Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
There was a lot of disappointment because it went on for so long, and the most important thing is that we're still very close friends with Bruce and Greg who started with us in the band, and when I hear a song or I see a picture, I think about the incredible person that Andy was, and how he made me laugh, and it was always fun to go to work, laugh, talk about music and football and so much more.
He was a wonderful man, and we miss him.
The local band Las Robertas will be responsible for opening the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you're familiar with her work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose her for the opening?
Yeah, the producers sent us some video suggestions, and this was the band we liked the most, so we can't wait to see what Las Robertas have to offer live, and it should be really exciting.
Why do you always change the lyrics at Yellow Ledbetter concerts?
This is a question for Ed, so I don't know.
He sings it and I think he uses the first thing that comes to his mind.
Who influenced you as a bass player?
There's so many of them.
Some of the first people that come to mind are Gezer Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukovsky...
There's so many of them, I could talk all day about the bass players I love.
How did Pearl Jam succeed in keeping grunge relevant even though it's out of fashion?
I think we all feel a little disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of the bands I mentioned earlier, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that came out at the same time, and if that's important now, I think that's great, because it's music worth listening to, and teams like Mudhoney are making music better than ever.
Your music used to be more somber, but now it's more positive.
How do you explain this change?
It's interesting because I think there are a few songs on the album that might seem lighter, but there are songs like The End or Just Breathe that are considered very dark, even though they can sound a little positive.
Both of them, when Ed played them, I cried when I listened to them, these songs are so dark.
I think when you're growing up, and you've had some kind of trauma in your life and you've lost a family member or a friend, those events start to affect your creativity and your music, and these two songs, of course, reflect that for me.
So I think you can be a happy person and still be able to make somber music.
