Fujimori was hospitalized again for medical examination.
Former President Alberto Fujimori was admitted to a state hospital on Tuesday for a test for loss of muscle strength in his legs, his family doctor said.
Fujimori, 72, who was sentenced to 25 years in prison for human rights abuses committed during his rule (1990-2000), suffers from several diseases, including tongue cancer, for which he has undergone four operations and is under observation.
Congressman Alejandro Aguinagá, who is his personal physician, told N TV that Fujimori will be examined in three days at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases to determine the cause of the pain and loss of strength in his lower extremities.
Aguinagá said that he thought Fujimori should be a candidate for pardon for humanitarian reasons; however, he said he did not want that because he knew he was innocent.
He had four operations for tongue cancer, lost 60 pounds [18 kg], and had other ailments, including severe erosive gastritis, pancreatic cysts, kidney stones, high blood pressure, and circulatory problems in his legs, the doctor said.
Fujimori has been in prison since September 2007, in the National Police Special Operations Directorate.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the murder of 25 people by the army's destruction squad, which operated in secret during the first years of his rule.
Mujica goes to Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official delegation led by Uruguayan President José Mujica and comprising several ministers and businessmen will arrive in Mexico this Tuesday to expand trade between the two countries and to begin negotiations on political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with his Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calderón, the most important item in a broad plan of meetings with political, commercial authorities and the Uruguayan community living in Mexico, according to a schedule released by the Uruguayan leadership.
The meeting of the two presidents in the city of Guadalajara will be "favorable for the exchange of information on the political relations between the two nations", the South American country's leadership said on its website.
According to local media, Mujica is seeking Calderon's support for Uruguay in the incident with France that occurred when French President Nicolas Sarkozy included the South American country on a list of tax havens at the G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that remain tax havens, a statement that provoked a protest from Uruguay and the recall of his ambassador to the European country for consultations.
Mexico has been the chairman since November of the G20, a group made up of the most highly developed and developing countries, and has, in fact, an agreement with the South American country since January of this year to exchange tax information to avoid double taxation.
The Uruguayan government has tried in recent years to speed up the conclusion of tax exchange agreements to get off the OECD's "gray list" of countries that do not use international tax cooperation standards.
As for the trade plan, Mexico and Uruguay have a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) in place since 2004, which has increased trade between the two countries.
The mustachioed plumber will be 3D with Super Mario 3D Land
Super Mario has been fighting tirelessly for over 25 years to save Princess Peach from Bowser's evil clutches, but never before has he done so in three dimensions: in Super Mario 3D Land, he will fight for the love of a girl in stereoscopic technology.
The edition, which will hit stores worldwide this month, was designed with the characteristics of the Nintendo 3DS handheld console in mind, which allows for three-dimensional play without the need for glasses.
"Mario is the hero who should tell how the stereoscopy will work without glasses", said Nintendo's head of press in Spain, Omar Alvarez, during the game's presentation in Madrid.
Alvarez said that Super Mario 3D Land is "Nintendo's first video game specifically designed for this platform", because to date successful products like Star Fox 64 3D or Zelda: Ocarina of Time 3D have been adaptations of existing games.
A Nintendo spokesperson stated that despite being in 3D, Super Mario 3D Land is an "affordable" video game that allows you to enjoy fast-paced and mobile play.
Alvarez said that Super Mario 3D Land contains two games in one: the first part is "simple" to attract less experienced users.
Once they start, most experts will go "round two" to levels that are more challenging this time.
In addition, users can choose in real time between "D aggressive" or one that only affects the depth of action, but which needs to be played in three dimensions to overcome various obstacles and "not give in to optical illusions".
This invasion of Super Mario in three dimensions also marks the return of the hero to a portable console, something that has not happened since 2005.
In this game, Nintendo winked at fans of the series and repeated the successful formula from previous games, a mustachioed plumber must walk through dangerous minefields to free Princess Peach.
However, the player will discover new moves, decorations, costumes and enemies, as well as "playing" Luigi.
