Park or mountain?
Architects agree to a bidding war after the bidding war
The 16 door competition has renewed debate over the role of the Colserol in Barcelona
In the mid-80s, at the height of the now defunct Barcelona Capital Corporation (BCC), this administration printed promotional flyers for Colserola.
The booklet described the mountain as a large park in the capital city of Barcelona.
Moreover, it was accompanied by a picture comparison to New York's Central Park.
With the death of the SCB, in 1987 the park once again took its place in the minds of many as the high point of Barcelona as the capital of Catalonia, one of the few that is oriented not north-south, but up (mountain) -down (sea).
The positioning of Colserola as a nature park contradicts this idea.
The prototype wasn't Central Park, it was Yellowstone, with a wild boar as Yogi the Bear.
That was until, in September, the council announced a huge competition of 16 contests for a host of other gates in Colserol.
Under the gate is the idea of a park, no doubt.
Either that or someone wants to put the goal on the field.
The question is, is it a park or a mountain?
The competitions, and their organizational aspect, and their impact on the city, are a topic for discussion by all Barcelona architects.
This is probably the most common theme discussed when two members of this clan of chosen people get to know each other in an elevator.
And this fact leads to one of the few coincidences between what the three architects in Barcelona say and the scientists who were there.
Miguel Roldan, Daniel Modolo and Mara Bayona: the competition is appropriate
For Roldán, once the coastline is reached, it becomes "necessary" to discuss the "front side of the mountain" when the proposal of the Ildefon Serda, the mountain with green apples, has not been implemented.
"You have to assume that the biggest park in Barcelona is the beach.
Among other things, because of its excellent accessibility.
