Modolo, like Roldán and Bayonne, who have experience in urban planning, called the proposal an "intellectual challenge" with "some dangers".
Risks arising from the "uncertainty of predicting public space" after the experience of the 80s, which ended on the Forum site "with its swan song".
The first fear is actually the limitation of where you can build.
"Limiting something is preparing for the next step", he means, the transition.
"We have to think about new urban planning tools because the current ones [regarding the General Capital Plan (GCP) ] can lead to real trouble".
Closer to the point, Modolo believes that simplifying the Colserola valley "can be understood as a park, Barcelona, rather than" as a purely topographical issue.
Modolo recalls that there is already work being done outside Kalserola that "should not be overlooked", although he is grateful for the opportunity the city offers his profession to get involved in the project "from the beginning".
Moreover, he understands that the proximity of the mountain to the city is a pass that allows architects to enter into the debate, but "he doubts" whether this technical profile is what should guide the interdisciplinary teams ("success", he argues) that were to create: "Architects should only be a tool".
Bayona hints that the answer to the question that sets the title of this section is difficult, as the rules of the competition lack a general view of the Colserola: "There were 16 intersecting competitions announced", he says, "in the sense of sea-mountain, but there is no longitudinal reading here to see and understand the area as a whole".
That makes him, at least in his case, decide to enter 16 contests.
On the other hand, a design for a single gate may overlap with the architect's design for adjacent gates.
From your point of view, the council must ensure that the strip directly above the Ronde de Delta provides a fully equipped area to create a smooth transition between the city and the green.
