"This information supports the hypothesis of a normal flight maneuver at the time of impact", he said.
At a press conference, SCT owner Perez Hakome listed six important elements in the investigation:
Visual flight:
According to aviation regulations, the flight was conducted under visual flight rules, which means that the crew must have visibility during flight and landing.
Weather conditions:
AICM reports indicated that the aircraft was heading for the border area between Mexico City and the State of Mexico, where layers of clouds were visible at low altitudes.
Selected routes:
It is possible that the team was looking for a lower altitude and higher visibility area in the Cuernavaca Valley because of the cloudy conditions.
The impact site.
The coordinates of the impact and the last radar record of the aircraft match, probably without loss of control or change of direction before the impact.
The scattered debris on a small area:
The information available so far indicates that the impact was on the front and the side lines.
The scattered debris indicates that the helicopter struck the ground in structural integrity.
No obvious signs of fire or explosion were detected:
There's no evidence of a shipwreck in the crash site, no evidence of an explosion or fire.
Recent studies suggest that there may have been multiple earthquakes.
During the site work, pieces of the aircraft were found at an altitude of 9,200 feet above sea level, the ground inclined from seven degrees to 30 degrees.
The images show the sequence in which it was destroyed along the way.
The information contains facts that seem to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple collisions with the ground.
After a thorough examination of a larger area than the designated area near the crash site, no scattered parts of the aircraft were found, which reinforces the assumption that the impact occurred in structural integrity.
MSS announces a program to find the gene for obesity
Social protection is leading the research to find the gene for obesity in children and young people, supported by IPN experts
The Mexican Social Security Institute (MSSI) announced that it is conducting a study to identify the gene for obesity in children and young adults, called the "Genetics of Childhood and Adolescent Obesity" protocol, which will provide a count of signs associated with being overweight.
In his statement, Miguel Cruz Lopez, head of the Biochemistry Division of the Specialized Hospital of the National Medical Center of the XXI Century, explained that a multidisciplinary team of therapists, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been assembled.
The team is assisted by specialists and graduate students from the National Institute of Health (NIPH) and the National Polytechnic Institute (NPI) Center for Scientific Research and Higher Education (CINVESTAV).
The population (registered or not) is invited to participate by visiting the participating MSSI sports centers in the Valley of Mexico, where children will be tested every Saturday morning at 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol was started at the sports center in Cuauhtémoc (in the west of Mexico City), and since October 8 the events are being held at the sports center in Nesahualcóatl (in the east of Mexico City).
Once the goal of 500 to 600 children has been reached, the study will continue at the Independence Sports Center (south of Mexico City) and finally at the Morelos Sports Center (north of Mexico City).
He explained that the purpose of this study was to understand the components and importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to determine the risk factor among children and young Mexicans to prevent the onset of chronic degenerative diseases.
World Diabetes Day is being observed on November 14 and the main goal is to get 3,000 children and adolescents aged 6 to 14 years old to fill out individual nutrition questionnaires with their parents' permission and supervision.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases to avoid risk factors that can lead to diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that on Saturday, anthropometric measurements (weight, height and waist circumference), blood pressure and glucose, fat, cholesterol and insulin levels, and genetic analysis (to identify genes that are linked to childhood obesity) will be performed on all participants.
Cruz Lopez said the study reflects health care professionals' concerns about alarming weight gain in children.
Medical studies conducted between 1999 and 2006 show that in just six years, there was an increase: 77 percent of boys were obese, 47 percent of girls were obese, and there was a significant increase in overweight", said MSSI.
He said the rationale for the search for markers was based on the fact that the population of the country is different from other peoples in its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican is 65 percent of American Indian descent, 30 percent of European descent, and five percent of African descent, and this condition has been linked to genes that are linked to diabetes and obesity.
He explained that the main cause of obesity is that the body is unable to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and it is stored as fat.
The researcher explained that the immediate benefit to participants is a comprehensive assessment of the children, which can reveal whether they are overweight or obese to any degree.
Even, he said, dark folds on the neck and forearms indicate a risk of metabolic disorders and even prediabetes.
The information is treated with utmost confidentiality, and the doctors give it in writing to the parents, who are then told all the measures and lifestyle changes that they need to make to avoid the disease.
Cruz Lopez explained that there are three main causes of overweight, obesity, and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle, or lack of daily physical activity, spending most of the day at home watching TV, and using transportation for short distances instead of walking.
It's also due to high calorie intake, which is the increased consumption of sugary drinks and carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with high fat and protein content and genetic predisposition, which is analyzed in this program.
The asphalt of UNAM will be able to avoid cracks
Raphael Herrera, a chemistry researcher at UNAM, developed polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mixture of the highest quality, resistant to environmental and temperature influences.
If the signals from road surfaces were taken into account, about 200,000 pits would need to be repaired each rainy season in the metropolitan area of the Valley of Mexico, says Rafael Herrera Najera, a chemistry researcher at UNAM, adding that if the construction and maintenance of paved roads are done correctly, the number of pits could be reduced or eliminated.
In his lecture Technological View of Pits, read as part of the International Year of Chemistry, it is reported that the laboratory he is responsible for is developing polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mixture with characteristics close to bitumen but with better resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Najera said this type of modified bitumen could be used in areas where the weather is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north, to improve the quality of roads and thus prevent pits.
He explained that bitumen, the heaviest part of oil, is a sequence of hydrocarbon molecules, some of high molecular weight called asphaltene, and others of low molecular weight called maltene, which together give the road surface its characteristic viscous behavior.
The viscous behavior of bitumen is that at high temperatures around 180 degrees it behaves like a liquid, at 120 it is very viscous, and at 50 degrees Celsius it remains almost solid, while at very low temperatures bitumen becomes brittle, he said.
This means that the resistance of the asphalt is not constant but varies throughout the day, depending on the natural conditions and temperature, said a chemical engineer.
The chemfake scientist noted that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered with flexible coatings, which are made up of six layers of material, the last three of which include bitumen.
Among the topmost layers is bitumen, made up of small stones that are lowered into the bitumen and then pressed.
Every rock that makes up this coating, he said, is buried in bitumen.
When vehicles are moving and applying effort, it helps the forces to be very well distributed on the road surface.
If it were modified asphalt, they would be even more distributed, said the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt, he added, is the last layer, called the wear layer, which is made of fine stone, actually sand also submerged in the asphalt.
Since this is a layer that will be in contact with the wheels of the vehicle, it must have greater resistance than asphalt and provide friction.
As part of the road surface that will receive and distribute these efforts, the wear layer also requires proper thickness, and the material from which it is made must be taken into account.
Weather, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also very important factors to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the condition of the asphalt.
When the soil is wet, water gets into the cover and it's hard for it to get out, so it causes all the layers of the cover to soften and hence form pits.
When pits form, he said, the wear layer first wears off and only then does it affect the bitumen, but the damage doesn't happen instantly, it's a process that should be addressed at the first sign of ongoing repair programs.
The National System of Researchers member also explained that transportation load is another important factor in the formation of holes, and therefore the thickness of each layer of coating must always be related to the transportation load and this requirement must be guaranteed to be met to prevent frequent pit formation.
Raphael Herrera said that there is still much to learn about bitumen, such as bitumen emulsions that are already on the market in other countries and even help repair pits easily and without the use of high temperatures.
