That was the work of the man who identified Alfonso Cano's body.
The forensic scientist from Cali made history as the man who confirmed the death of Alfonso Cano.
The work of these employees is key.
On November 4, CTI forensic scientist Cali made history as the man who confirmed the identity of FARC leader Alfonso Cano by matching his fingerprints.
Of the seven forensic scientists working at CTI, this week's watch was taken by Eleazar Gonzalez, a man from Puerto Tejada who has spent 21 years in the field of forensic investigation.
Early in his career, González worked in Choco towns, where he often had to travel for more than five days through the jungle to reach the location of the bodies that needed to be identified.
In 2000 he moved to the Valleys and after completing the relevant courses he became a specialist in criminology, where he studied the friction of the skin, i.e. palms and stones.
During the week of Eleazar's operation to identify the man known as Alfonso Cano, he was told to take clothes for no more than three days.
Something big was coming.
He arrived on a helicopter from Caucus to Palmyra Friday night.
He knew he would have to identify two bodies, and one of them was supposed to belong to a man who had led the world's oldest guerrilla war, so they asked him to take ten prints of Guillermo Leon Science (his real name).
However, when he arrived with his research team at the site of the body, he did not recognize it by its appearance; it was very different from what was shown in the media.
He was beardless, dressed like a local farmer, no glasses, and significantly thinner.
But the prints don't lie.
Using a magnifying glass, ink, a shovel, and a flashlight, Eleazar matched the body's fingerprints to those found in the photos.
His eyes were not deceived: it was Alfonso Cano.
That night, a representative of Puerto Tejada was asked to confirm to Secretary of Defense Juan Carlos Pinson that he was the head of the RPCC.
Fingerprints are coming up .
For a specialist in the field of fingerprinting of the Sijin unit in Cali, the recognition received from President Juan Manuel Santos by Eleazar González at a press conference on the operation against Cano is particularly significant.
A lot of people don't know what we do.
Dental surgery is a rigorous science, no mistakes, and it can be a key tool in solving crimes.
In addition to identifying bodies, fingerprint specialists are involved in the investigation of crimes such as theft and murder, and identify detainees.
When arrested, many criminals have fake IDs or no papers.
We're gonna pull their prints and run them through the database.
The investigator said that in the case of theft, he had to take a piece of the wall of the house because the thief leaned his hands on it to grab a safe full of jewels and money.
"Walls are hard to work with because they are not a comfortable surface to take fingerprints on, but in this case we can take a picture of the entire palm and identify the criminal who was involved in several thefts", he says.
Prints also help rule out or establish the involvement of suspects in murder cases.
A man was recently found dead with liquor bottles around him.
The investigation revealed that a relative may have been involved in the crime and that the fingerprints on the bottle did indeed match.
While that doesn't guarantee he was the killer, it does prove he was at the scene.
A fingerprint specialist at CTI explained that a chemical or physical reagent is applied to the fingerprint sites.
When they appear, a spatula or tape is used to remove them.
After that, the fingerprint images are sent to Asif, which is a database of criminals, or entered into the registry.
"The problem is that we still have a lot of undocumented Colombians", the CTI expert said.
He explained that it wasn't like CSI.
Just like not everything that glitters is gold, not everything you touch leaves a mark on you.
However, if possible, a comparison is made.
