Japanese Prime Minister Yashihiko Noda warned on Tuesday that Japanese authorities would intervene in the currency market if the yen continued to rise.
We will intervene as we did last time if we find excessive volatility in the yen exchange rate, Mr. Noda explained to the Senate.
On Tuesday, the yen rose to near historic levels, prompting the Japanese authorities to intervene on October 31.
On that day, Tokyo sold the yen for dollars on a massive scale to devalue the Japanese currency, which had set a new record for strength since 1945.
But since then, the yen has been rising steadily, driven by purchases by investors who see it as a "safe haven" in these troubled times of global economic downturn and the European debt crisis.
On Tuesday, the dollar fell below 77 yen and the euro fell below the symbolic bar of 105 yen, close to the level that triggered the last intervention.
On the eve of the 2008-2009 financial crisis, the dollar was worth about 120 yen, and the euro was worth more than 160 yen.
The growth of the Japanese currency is hurting Japanese exports, as it makes Japanese products more expensive and reduces the amount of income Japanese firms earn from abroad when converting into national currency.
"Japan is struggling to rebuild itself" after the March 11 earthquake and tsunami that devastated the northeastern Tohoku region, stressed Mr. Noda, who fears the yen's rise will kill the fragile seed of recovery.
The world's third-largest economy resumed growth in the third quarter -1.5% year-on-year for the first time, driven by rising exports and consumption by disaster-hit households.
But the prime minister feels that the high price of the yen does not reflect "Japan's fundamental economic indicators".
Finance Minister Jun Azuumi urged the Bank of Japan (BoJ), which opened a two-day meeting of its monetary policy council on Tuesday, to take all necessary steps to weaken the yen.
But Deputy Governor Hirohide Yamaguti warned that the Bank of Japan had already taken "appropriate steps", making it clear that no further easing was to be expected on Wednesday.
At its last meeting in late October, the issuer increased its purchase of Treasury bonds by 5,000 million yen (47 thousand million euros), raising to 55,000 thousand million yen (519 thousand million euros) the ceiling of the amounts it allocates to purchase various financial instruments to saturate the securities market.
