Energy policy:
Facts must prevail over dogma .
If there is one issue that cannot be decided after a brief discussion or under the influence of emotion, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affect the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is a healthy trend that election rallies become a reason to reflect on the role and place of nuclear power.
The debate will not bear fruit until all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the options proposed are examined.
France must base its opinion on objective facts and rational data.
Now, with seven billion people on the planet, the demographic growth will double the electricity demand by 2050, unless a huge portion of the world's population is deprived of essential elements.
During the same period, it will be necessary to address the growing shortage of fossil fuels to continue to generate electricity on a permanent basis, while also keeping in mind the critical need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate imbalance, a topic that has largely disappeared from environmental debate.
The Fukushima accident doesn't change any of those factors.
That's why Germany is alone in its decision to abandon nuclear energy.
This is not the case in Belgium, which is making its decision dependent on the need to find a source capable of replacing nuclear energy, or in Switzerland, which intends to build only the most modern reactors.
On the other hand, the United Kingdom, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil - these are just a few of the countries that are determined to continue their projects.
The United States decided after Fukushima to add one more to its fleet, resuming construction of the station, which had been interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
Although Germany's renewable energy model is sometimes cited as an example, the reality is contrary to this argument.
The choice of Berlin will result in increased electricity costs, increased energy dependence, exacerbated by increased demand for imported gas, in particular from Russia, a jump in carbon dioxide emissions due to the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, all these unpleasant effects will be felt.
The example of Denmark is worth considering.
Europe's champion in turbine construction, which generates 30% of its electricity, it is also the largest consumer of coal and gas because of intermittent wind; which makes carbon dioxide emissions and electricity prices respectively 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the other hand, thanks to our consistent energy policies, our neighbors pay 40% more for electricity than French households.
In a globalised economy, energy prices are a key factor in competitiveness and the maintenance of industrial equipment in the country, so French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
As a result, any significant reduction in nuclear power will lead to a huge increase in the cost of electricity, which will make illusory the beautiful claims of the new industrialization of our country and the protection of purchasing power.
A price most French people refuse to pay, especially since they have no objection to this type of energy in principle.
It should be recalled that the country's energy policy has made it possible to create an industry with 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Strongly export-oriented, it attracts a whole host of small and medium-sized enterprises specialising in international trade and creates many jobs that cannot be moved to another industry.
If France were to abandon nuclear energy, it would have to sacrifice a large number of these enterprises and lose 6 billion euros a year from French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
What kind of electrical engineer would order an EPR designed to last 60 years if the manufacturer was going to shut down?
To solve the energy equation, we must recognize that there are no divine or diabolical sources of energy.
Areva's development of low-carbon solutions, both nuclear and renewable, demonstrates the complementarity of energy sources.
For nuclear energy , maintaining the highest level of safety is undoubtedly vital .
In France, we have a security authority that exercises uncompromising and transparent control over existing energy centres such as Flamandville.
Our teams, whose professionalism is widely recognized, are full of the same obsession with security.
In the last 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three major accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions, but without any human or environmental impact.
In Chernobyl, the reactor's design and unforgivable human error led to tragedy.
Some people in Fukushima seem to forget that the accident was the result of two natural disasters of unprecedented force that killed tens of thousands.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident, as it did from the two before it.
The result of this step and the cooperation between the security authorities, operators and French and German designers, EPR, is a project that will help to combat such phenomena.
Since it is being considered by all energy professionals who want to build a reactor, stopping its construction in Flamandville would be a great gift to Areva's and EDF's competitors, paving the way for them to gain leadership in the inevitable development of nuclear energy.
It is necessary and legitimate to seek the best combination of energy sources for our country, but it would be irresponsible to allow emotions, dogmas and biased maneuvers to prevail in a dispute that is so important to the economic, social and financial position of our country.
Immigration - A Burden or a Benefit for the Economy?
Nicolas Sarkozy's immigration policy has been criticized from all sides - overloading police, judicial and administrative services with a policy of numbers and its compatibility with France's self-proclaimed status as a "human rights state".
Then there was the administrative harassment of foreign students, which made headlines when the Minister of the Interior (Liberation of 23 May) declared that France "does not need foreign talents, masons and waiters".
But it's rarely analyzed from an economic standpoint.
The right and the left are largely in agreement on this issue.
On the right, Jacques Chirac declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed would not be a problem in a country with 2 million foreign workers", while on the left, Michel Rocard explained in 1990 that France "cannot accept the poor from all over the world".
The only difference is the level of generosity .
In 2005, the fear of an invasion of the territory of the Polish waterworks horde was felt by both the left and the right.
Both sides see immigration as a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is the level of generosity they're willing to show to immigrants.
In his programme, François Hollande confined himself to the mundane, saying that "working together will solve our immigration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden and a problem can be an electoral advantage, but economically it is very costly.
As economists Ian Goldin and Jeffrey Cameron remind us in their recent book summarizing the latest data on immigration (People of Interest: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pages), there is broad consensus among scholars about the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries that host immigrants.
Restricting immigration leads to slower growth and lower employment.
Fears of immigrant influence are based on the notion that they can replace local workers, especially low-skilled ones, by causing lower wages.
But experience shows that in reality, immigrants are more likely to supplement than replace the local workforce, doing jobs for which there is a shortage of local labor.
Unskilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract local labour, while the most skilled work in dynamic sectors where training is not linked to job offers.
Positive impact on wages
Just as it would be difficult for a surgeon to work in a country where there is a shortage of anesthesiologists, the complementarity between locals and immigrants means that the influx of immigrants has a positive impact on the wages of local workers.
Giovanni Peri calculated that a 1% increase in migration flows leads to a 0.6-0.9% increase in real long-term wages.
And that's without considering the fact that the diversity that immigrants bring to the table is driving innovation and economic growth (among American Nobel laureates, a large proportion of naturalized immigrants, and Google, Intel, Paypal and Yahoo - all founded by immigrants).
Migrants also contribute a net benefit to social security systems, contributing on average 1% of the total budgets of European countries.
The World Labour Organization estimates that in Germany, for example, an immigrant who arrives at the age of 30 will bring an average of 150,000 euros of net income (income minus expenses) to the state budget in his lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy was about to grab the missing growth points with his teeth at the beginning of his term.
The teeth they used to scare off immigrants had the opposite effect.
Europe has invented democracy, we have to understand European democracy.
Democracy is a valuable asset, but it is also fragile.
The European continent must remember that, having invented it in Athens over two thousand years ago, in the 20th century it has survived the tragedies of World War I, totalitarian regimes, the Holocaust, the Gulag, as well as Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal and colonels in Greece.
Some believed that for democracy to finally triumph over its enemies, it was enough to arrange voting and make it as direct as possible.
It's been known since the days of Napoleon the Little that this comes from superficial thinking.
Universal voting, while a necessary condition of democracy, is not sufficient and may even become "an instrument of repression", as the Republican philosopher Etienne Vashor once said.
No, democracy requires much more than that - public space, public spirit, values, organization, separation and control of power, education, enlightenment, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The European crisis we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but first and foremost it is a political crisis and a crisis of democracy.
In this respect, the palinody of the truth-false Greek referendum will have a double exposure effect, demonstrating both the need for a major policy change and the unpleasant sense of its impossibility and inconsistency.
This duality must be understood in order to overcome it.
The truth is that the front line of the fight for democracy has now shifted and, according to many, the Republican soldiers are now aiming in the wrong direction.
We will gain nothing by demanding a series of national referendums, organised as needed and in a chaotic order.
A carte blanche for an absolute European monarch or a bound-foot leap into the abyss of nationalism - what a choice for a citizen!
No, we do not dream of a guillotine, but of the implementation of a common, clear and continuous choice and democracy, this time at a European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal, and it is not known how many more we will have to list, because there is only one crisis, the crisis of Europe.
Europe as a whole is under the dictates of markets and rating agencies, suffering from its own weakness and lack of solidarity.
The whole of Europe is humiliated on the international stage.
Many are concerned about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe, but Europe as a whole is gradually losing its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations.
It is urgent to return the governance of the European project to popular sovereignty.
Because only by working together can Europeans reduce the burden of debt on everyone, free themselves from markets and prepare for the future by investing in it.
The way out of the crisis will require European-wide solutions, and they cannot be adopted without full democratic legitimacy, without leading us to disaster.
After a long discussion of this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone now demands a European economic government.
Let's just do it like that.
But to imagine it without the stronger economic, political and democratic integration that has been achieved by the citizen is another madness and another deadlock.
We must start a new phase of European construction.
To establish a republic in France, it was necessary to "create" republicans.
A revolution of interests would not be enough.
That lesson is still valid.
We must build a Europe united on an economic level.
This can only be done by creating a more democratic Europe at a political level, a genuine European people's sovereignty.
To create Europe, let us create Europeans.
