The terror front is spreading from the Sahara to Nigeria .
Paris is concerned about the Islamic Maghreb's ties to Boko Haram.
Long-standing links between the Al-Qaeda in the Muslim Maghreb (Aqmi) terrorist group and the Boko Haram sect in Nigeria have been confirmed.
On Sunday, Algeria's deputy foreign minister Abdelkader Messaghel even said that Algerians now believe it.
"The way these two organizations are working and the intelligence reports show that they are actively cooperating", he explained, without elaborating.
Paris seems to have come to similar conclusions.
The investigation into the kidnapping of two Frenchmen in Niger in January revealed two connections.
Abducted from a restaurant in Niamey by people close to Aqmi, Antoine de Lecourt and Vincent Delory were apparently killed the next day along with several of their captors in an operation carried out by French special forces.
Among the debris left after the operation, French and Nigerian investigators found several phone SIM cards belonging to the terrorists.
The axis of terror
The analysis of the calls revealed several recipients in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
Two numbers are of particular interest to investigators, according to Radio France Internationale (RFI); one points to a Nigerian who has lived in Maiduguri, the birthplace of Boko Haram, a city in northern Nigeria, for a long time, and another to a man allegedly close to Aqmi and the sect.
"This is a step forward, but we must wait for more solid evidence before talking about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram".
"But it is possible".
"It has been known for years that the sect receives financial and ideological support from outside and that it is becoming more and more active", says Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, this support has become increasingly evident in Boko Haram's actions and statements and in its methods, which now include the use of suicide bombers and increasingly sophisticated explosive devices of the same type used by Aqmi.
The international community, led by Washington, is now pressuring Abuja to address the problems posed by Boko Haram.
The fact is that the Nigerian authorities have traditionally viewed this group as a community of educated people who are of no interest.
It was a quick success.
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri with a mosque, school and imam-fundamentalist Muhammad Yusuf, Boko Haram - which in Hausa means "Western education is a sin" - preaches the establishment of an Islamic emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria.
In this poor region, the organization has achieved rapid success.
It is politicised and demands strict adherence to Sharia law, and its activists have launched a struggle against the wicked central government.
It's targeting churches, bars and government agencies.
In 2009, Boko Haram activists were particularly active, carrying out numerous attacks on police stations.
Abuja's response, as usual, has been uncompromising.
The army blocked the city and left behind 800 dead.
Muhammad Yusuf, captured alive, was killed in prison.
Now the sect is radicalizing and expanding beyond its northern foothills.
Last Christmas, she claimed responsibility for an attack that killed 80 people in Jos and then another in Abuja.
In June, Boko Haram carried out the first suicide attack on a police headquarters in Abuja.
In August, a local UN mission will be their first international destination.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa, which runs from Mauritania through Nigeria to Somalia, is now a concern for all security experts.
Today, with Aqmi entrenched in Mali and Niger and Somali al-Shabaab operating in Kenya, Boko Haram poses a new threat to the continent.
Last week, during a conversation with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé warned of the danger of Boko Haram and expressed his willingness to share all available information.
The world as seen by the Republican presidential candidates
When it comes to China, Iran and aid to Israel, Mitt Romney, Herman Kane and Rick Perry are all competing for simplicity and incompetence.
Can a crisis-weakened America lead a complex world with simple, or rather simplified, ideas?
If you listen to the Republican presidential candidates, the voters might believe it.
For days, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, Rick Perry and others have been making loud but lackluster foreign policy statements that have traditionally been Republican strong points.
The slogans about China, Iran and helping Israel are often mixed up.
Mitt Romney, who has the best chance of being nominated by the "Old Good Party", threatened to file a complaint against the Chinese at the WTO and accuse them of "manipulating their currency - it's a sensitive subject for America, irritated by the migration of entire industries to Asia.
"Even worse if it leads to a trade war", he said.
John Huntsman, Obama's former ambassador to China and the only candidate with an understanding of complex foreign policy, couldn't resist a position that indulges emotion.
He called for a firm but constructive dialogue with Beijing (Obama's current position).
But Huntsman, who's at the bottom of the ratings, has gone unheard.
It 's Reagan style .
Romney also vowed military strikes on Iran if sanctions failed to stop its nuclear program.
"If I get elected, I will stop Iran", he announced.
"If Obama is re-elected, they'll have a bomb".
He also promised to increase military aid to Israel, accusing Obama of not keeping his promises to that partner.
Entrepreneur Herman Kane, second in the candidates' ranking, has shown a discouraging ignorance.
He recently called for confronting the Chinese military threat because Beijing is trying to build a nuclear power - apparently unaware that China has had one since 1964!
Texas Governor Rick Perry, who supports Israel and wants military strikes on Iran, says he's willing to use the U.S. military in Mexico against drug cartels.
The use of torture of terrorism suspects, which Obama banned in 2009, is also recommended by Kane, Perry and candidate Michelle Bachman.
All of this is a far cry from 2008 Republican nominee John McCain, a foreign policy heavyweight.
The president's opponents say Reagan had simple ideas too and that he won the Cold War.
They remind us that Obama was an amateur himself and that he had to tone down his fight against terrorism.
They rightly insist on the failure of his naive dialogue with Iran, the premature withdrawal of his "boys" from Iraq, his ruses in Libya, which earned him a reputation as a weak politician.
But the offensive is not so easy.
The population sees a positive balance of national security under Obama, who eliminated bin Laden.
After Iraq, it doesn't believe in military interventions that get stuck in the sand.
And when he says that America needs to be economically restructured to regain its leadership, Obama is right.
Nord Stream, the new gateway for Russian gas to Europe.
The Nord Stream gas pipeline connecting Western Europe and Russia directly to the bottom of the Baltic Sea has been launched.
It is designed to supply the equivalent of 30 million households with gas.
Gazprom, Russia's giant gas producer, wanted to celebrate with a bang.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part last Tuesday on the Baltic shores, between an orchestra performance and fine dining, in the opening of Nord Stream, the new gas pipeline that directly connects Russia and Germany underwater.
German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Francois Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mart Rutte have all turned a symbolic valve that controls the flow of Russian gas into the Western European grid.
The new gas pipeline will bring 27,5 million cubic meters of additional gas to Western Europe each year through the first 1224 km pipeline connecting the Leningrad region with the land of Mecklenburg-Pomeranian.
The second pipeline should be ready by the end of 2012, providing a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, equivalent to all of France's gas consumption.
And the possibility of a third pipeline in the same direction is already being discussed.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge project is a victory.
The project met fierce resistance from Poland and the Baltic states.
The Nord Stream will indeed allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
These two countries will lose some of their power: they will find it harder to influence Russia, threatening to close access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not stop comparing the Nord Stream with the new "German-Soviet Pact", hinting at an alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That means it's a politically sensitive issue.
By supporting this Russian project, Western Europe is seeking greater security of its supplies.
But at the cost of depriving Europe of energy, because the project created a gap between Eastern and Western Europe.
Russia has managed in less than five years to achieve its understanding of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries that consume large volumes of gas and whose own reserves are already running out.
"This gas pipeline is part of our cooperation with Russia, it is a new artery that organically connects us", said François Fillon, opening the pipeline, demonstrating the importance of large gas contracts both politically and economically.
This explains the wide smiles on the faces of Gazprom executives who were present in large numbers at Lubmin, the gas arrival point.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical feat.
The underwater pipeline is made of steel, encased in concrete to protect it from the anchors of ships.
It lies on the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 meters.
To build it, we had to bypass the minefields left over from World War II.
"The hundred had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution", said Jens Müller, a spokesman for the North Stream company.
Many steps were also needed to protect the fauna and flora.
The pipeline is a long metal snake, weighing the weight of 242 Eiffel Towers, with no gaps along its entire length, no valves, and no service stations.
The control platform was planned to be built in the Swedish area, but the project managers refused it because Sweden was not happy that the Russian state company would settle permanently on its shores.
"In the event of an accident, we can cut off the gas flow in less than a minute", says Jens Müller.
So, in the event of a leak, the gas in the pipeline will be released into the air.
But that seems unlikely to the designers who designed the seams to only leak once every 100,000 years.
The gas pipeline will be monitored by an underwater robot that pulls the ship for external observation, as well as by an apparatus that circulates inside the pipeline.
The cigar-shaped device is inserted into a 1 meter diameter pipe and pushed forward by a gas stream.
When it arrives after three full days of travel at 10 feet per second, it gives precise information about any metal deformation.
The pipeline was designed to operate for 50 years without the slightest need for repair.
The gas circulates only at its pressure.
It's 200 bar on departure and 100 bar on arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the capital.
The rest are German companies E.ON and BASF (each 15.5%), Dutch Gasunie and French Group GDF Suez (each 9.0%).
These five companies formed a joint venture called Nord Stream, which was tasked with building and operating the pipeline.
Its headquarters are in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Then Gazprom leased it to this company for twenty years with the possibility of extending the entire volume of gas transportation.
"Gazprom will pay for the full volume, regardless of how much gas is actually transported", says Jens Müller.
The gas pipeline was financed by 30% of the shareholders and 70% of the bank loans.
The total cost of the work will be 7.4 billion euros for the two pipelines.
GDF Suez will invest around 240 million.
But the minority shareholders are confident that they will recoup their costs because Gazprom takes all the risks.
The gas pipeline runs from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin to a sandy beach with coniferous trees.
The 15 foot high valves form the gas outlet terminal.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas before it is pumped into German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal has been receiving one million cubic meters of gas every hour.
At full power, it's going to be 3 million an hour, and in 2012, it's going to be 6 million.
The Moleskine branded notebook
Moleskine, created by an Italian company 15 years ago, will bring back the taste of writing.
It has the smell of adventure, hours spent writing by candlelight.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable by its rectangular black cover, its rubber, its yellowish-white pages, which seem to have turned yellow with time.
However, the Moleskine notebook, as we know it today, was born in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, has decided to launch designer notebooks.
Maria Sebregondi, the company's consultant at the time, took responsibility for launching the new product.
The notebook is inspired by the old production technique, the moleskin - a lacquered cotton fabric used, for example, to cover benches.
It is said that this type of notebook is highly valued by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine brought to today's taste an old and forgotten thing that was a cult for avant-garde artists until the 20th century", said Maria Sebregondi, who has since become a brand manager at Modo Modo.
Success has come.
From 2006 to 2010, sales increased by 25% to 12.7 million units.
We've come a long way from the early years when we only produced 3,000 notebooks.
Moleskine has crossed the borders of Italy and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the USA.
It's hard to profile a typical buyer because the notebook is equally appealing to business people, students and freelancers.
Moleskine's customers are cosmopolitan, broad-minded and educated.
A small Italian company that started with only 12 employees now has 100 and two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her notebooks in Fnac bookstores, in small towns and has gained wide recognition.
"We followed the spirit of the times and this new need for writing, despite the advent of e-mail", explains Maria Sebregondi.
This distinctive cultural trait has accompanied the development of Moleskine; the brand recently organized an exhibition "The Circular Way", where architects and artists showcased their own notebooks.
In August, he also launched leopard art covers for the Locarno film festival.
Leveraging its success and cultural aura, Moleskine diversified its products, which now include bags, pens, computer bags, and all kinds of supports.
A success that was enviable: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, which wrote a new page in the history of Moleskine.
