"In 15 years, significant progress has been made".
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not two times, but three times higher".
"But there is still much work to be done".
I must say that there are still many obstacles to employment for people with disabilities.
Among them , the elderly are more numerous: 37% are over 50 (an average of 17%).
They have rather low qualifications: 80% do not have a bachelor's degree, and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very high, at 85% for disabled people, compared with 38% on average.
In short, these are all criteria that make it very difficult to return to work and that are the core of the problem", says Christian Grapen, CEO of Tremplin, an association set up in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Here are some of the obstacles.
There's no need to talk about a mentality that's changing, but it's changing too slowly.
A study commissioned by the Cité by IMS-Entreprendre in April found that managers surveyed had low knowledge of disability and "imagined themselves as people in wheelchairs or mentally or mentally disabled".
The result is that private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from the target of 6% disabled workers set by the 1987 law.
The latest known figures for 2008 are 2.6%.
"Today we are at about 3%", says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, an organization responsible for collecting taxes on companies that do not comply with the law.
Evidence: the number of 'taxable' organisations, as well as the amounts paid, fell between 2007 and 2011 from 59 000 to 46 000 organisations (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law that raised the tax put a lot of pressure on companies", explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects the rise in awareness, particularly in large enterprises".
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of organisations with 20 to 49 employees have disabled workers, compared with 82% of organisations with 100 to 199 employees.
